<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Trade Pullback for Security with Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Cabinet Secretary Danny
Naveh Monday denied Israel has territorial ambition in Lebanon,
saying its only desire is to safeguard the security of residents
near the northern border.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Radio, Naveh said a way would be
found to reach a deal with Lebanese government to ensure southern
Lebanon does not serve as the basis for guerrilla attacks against
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Naveh, who just returned from a visit to Paris, said that
Syria, which has 40,000 troops stationed in Lebanon, is the main
power in solving the current standoff in South Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Naveh and Uzi Arad, the foreign policy adviser of Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, were in France for a
one-day tour reportedly because of diplomatic signals that Syria
is interested in renewing negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
However, no details about the diplomatic mission have been
released.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Uri Lubrani, Israel's top official for Lebanon
affairs, said Monday that he backs the government initiative to
withdraw from Lebanon. However, he said it was just "the
beginning of the process" and Syria must be part of the process.
</P>
<P>
Israeli President Ezer Weizman also expressed his hope that
Netanyahu and Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai would
succeed in their efforts to pull Israeli troops out of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israeli troops are engaged in an attrition war with resistance
forces in south Lebanon where they carved out a security zone in
1985 to prevent guerrillas from cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Their occupation has been costly - in 1997 more than 100
Israeli soldiers died in fightings or in accidents in Lebanon. And
last week, three Israeli soldiers were killed by a long-range
Hezbollah mortar attack on their outpost in the western sector of
the security zone.
</P>
<P>
There has been strong public appeal in Israel for a unilateral
troop withdrawal from Lebanon. However, the Netanyahu government
has been insisting that security arrangements be worked out with
Beirut before Israeli troops pull back.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu and Mordechai said Sunday that Israel was willing to
fulfill U.N. Security Council Resolution 425 which calls for
Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon, in exchange for guarantees that
it would not be attacked by guerrillas from across the border.
</P>
<P>
Observers noted that this was the first time that Netanyahu had
made a direct reference to the U.N. resolution. Netanyahu and
Mordechai are expected to elaborate the government position on
Lebanon in separate trips to Europe this week.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu will be visiting Norway, which has peacekeepers in
south Lebanon. Mordechai has plans to travel to France, which has
long-standing interests in Lebanon and is a member of the
International Monitoring Committee in South Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
