<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albania Calls for Peaceful End to Kosov Conflict: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Albanian Prime Minister Fatos Nano
said on Monday that he hopes to end the conflict in Kosov, of
Yugoslavia, through peaceful and diplomatic means.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press, Nano said his government is
following closely the developments in Kosov, where ethnic
Albanians account for about 90 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
An autonomous province of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia
since 1989, Kosov declared independent in 1991. But except for
Albania, no other countries have so far given their recognition.
</P>
<P>
As a latest development, a Yugoslavian Interior Ministry police
patrol was ambushed last Saturday in Glogovac, Kosovo, resulting
in the death of four policemen and 16 attackers.
</P>
<P>
The event highlighted the fact that there should be no more
delay in efforts to end the conflict and the Albanian government
was ready to play its role in the process, Nano said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
