<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPPCC Receives First Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The proposal, calling for accelerating the development of risk
investment in China, has been raised by the Central Committee
of the China Democratic National Construction Association (CDNCA).
</P>
<P>
A member of CPPCC National Committee's Subcommittee for
Examining Proposals described the proposal as a "significant" one
showing great foresight. It has already received attention from
the State Planning Commission and the State Science and Technology
Commission.
</P>
<P>
Global competition, in final analysis, is one of national
strength and of science and technology. To gain a favorable
position in this competition, China must introduce the experience
of other countries in risk investment and promote high-tech
development, the proposal says.
</P>
<P>
Risk investment refers to investing in the research and
development of new and high technology having the risk of
failure.
</P>
<P>
The proposal is the result of one-year investigations led by
Cheng Siwei, a noted expert on management.
</P>
<P>
"China is a developing country, and the level of high
technology is closely related to its social progress and economic
take-off in the next century," said Xiong Dafang, head of the
Investigation and Study Department under the CDNCA Central
Committee who has contributed to the proposal.
</P>
<P>
At present, risk investment in China remains on a small scale
and sources of such investment are limited.
</P>
<P>
The proposal suggests that development of risk investment be
made a fundamental government policy to promote scientific
advancement and economic growth and that the policy be
incorporated into the country's medium and long-term development
program for national economic growth and social progress.
</P>
<P>
The proposal also suggests that regulations on the management
of risk investment be worked out as soon as possible so that the
rights of risk investment companies will be better protected.
</P>
<P>
Making proposals is an important way for CPPCC members to
participate in and deliberate state affairs. Over the past five
years, the CPPCC Eighth National Committee received more than
11,700 proposals.
</P>
<P>
Up to five o'clock this afternoon, 172 proposals had been
submitted to the First Session of the CPPCC Ninth National
Committee.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
