<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-02 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Government Organs Asked to Cut Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti government organs have
been asked to reduce their expenditures by 25 percent due to a
drop of oil revenues caused by price plunge on world market, the
Kuwait News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted director of Finance Ministry's Budget
Department, Abdel Wahab, as saying that the government bodies were
required to cut their spending in the remaining period of the
current fiscal year (July 1, 1997 to June 30, 1998).
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of the Kuwaiti revenues are from oil
exports. The government's budget predicted oil revenues at 2.6
billion dinars (8.58 billion U.S. dollars) in the current fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
The budgeted expenditure, on the other hand, was 3.2 billion
Kuwait dinars (10.56 billion U.S. dollars). But Kuwaiti crude
prices dropped one to two dollars per barrel on the world market
over the past four months from the budgeted 12 dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf country was granted a new quota of 2.19 million
barrels per day from 2 million during the first half of 1998 under
a new output ceiling agreed by the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the anticipated increase in revenue was not achieved
because oversupply, warm winter, southeast Asia economic crisis
and Iraq's possible return to the oil market have conspired to
depress oil prices to their lowest level in four years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
