<HEADLINE> British Govt to Make Concessions After Rural March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- British government promised on
Monday to have more consideration of the farmers rights after a
quarter of a million protesters marched through central London on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The government has been listening and has been making changes
in policy and we shall continue to do so," a government spokesman
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The protesters, from every corner of the country, protested
the government for policies which are threatening the rural way of
life, including the ban of selling beef on bones and the proposed
ban on fox-hunting.
</P>
<P>
But the spokesman said Prime Minister Tony Blair had not
addressed the idea of setting up a separate ministry to handle
countryside issues, or reshaping his government to defuse the rural
protest.
</P>
<P>
Despite massive support from Labor MPs, the bill to ban
fox-hunting, introduced by Labor backbencher Michael Foster, is
thought certain to fail because of lack of parliamentary time.
</P>
<P>
"There is no question of government time in this session for
the fox hunting bill," Blair's spokesman said, describing the
measure as not a priority for the government's future legislative
plans.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that farmers were facing a real problem because
of falling incomes, caused partly by the strong pound sterling.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the government unveiled a string of concessions on
rural issues, including extra cash for farmers and more protection
for village schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
