<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Registers Strong Gain in Personal Income in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. personal income
increased a strong 0.6 percent in January, the Commerce Department
reported here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The increase was bolstered by cost-of-living growth for Social
Security recipients and pay raises for federal employees. However,
even if without those and other special factors, incomes would
have increased a still healthy 0.5 percent, according to the
department. Incomes had increased 0.4 percent in December and 0.7
percent in November respectively.
</P>
<P>
Consumer spending, meanwhile, climbed up by a moderate 0.4
percent in January, no change from that of December and November.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the United States recorded a 3.8 percent growth in its
GDP, which was the strongest in nine years. The Asian financial
chaos is expected dampen U.S. growth this year by cutting American
export sales and encouraging more imports to the United States.
</P>
<P>
All categories of income increased in January, including the
most important wages and salaries, up 0.7 percent. Also higher
were transfer payments, such as Social Security and welfare, and
business owners' income, interest and dividend income.
</P>
<P>
The disposable, or after-tax, incomes shot up by 0.9 percent,
the largest increase in 19 months. Because after-tax incomes rose
more swiftly than spending, the savings rate rose to 4.2 percent
of disposable income, the most in seven months and up from 3.9
percent in December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
