<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's SPD Names Schroeder as Chancellor Candidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Germany's main opposition Social
Democratic Party (SPD) today formally endorsed Gerhard Schroeder,
premier of the Lower Saxony state, as its candidate to challenge
Chancellor Helmut Kohl in the national elections on September 27
this year.
</P>
<P>
The nomination was decided by the SPD presidency as well as its
executive committee at two separate meetings in Bonn on Monday,
one day after Schroeder scored a huge victory for the SPD at the
regional elections of Lower Saxony on Sunday by winning 47.9
percent of the vote, while Kohl's Christian Democratic Union (CDU)
coming in at only 35.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The state election victory has enabled Schroeder to win over
his party chairman Oskar Lafontaine in their one-year rivalry over
the SPD chancellor candidacy.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder, 53, is described by the German press as a more
dangerous challenger to Kohl because he has more chances to win
vital centrist votes much needed by Kohl's centre-right ruling
coalition.
</P>
<P>
As an active proponent of high-technology investments and a
former board member of Germany's largest carmaker Volkswagen AG,
Schroeder says he understands the challenges faced by German
businesses in global markets and pledges to undertake reforms to
improve Germany's competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
And as one of five children raised by a war widow who earned a
living as a cleaning lady, Schroeder also says he wants to
preserve many of the country's welfare programs at a time when
Germany faces a post-war record unemployment of 4.8 million
people.
</P>
<P>
With Schroeder as the SPD chancellor candidate, German
commentators are now predicting a much harder re-election battle
for Kohl whose popularity has been trailing the SPD politician in
all recent opinions polls.
</P>
<P>
Despite Schroeder's victory in Lower Saxony, the CDU today
vowed to stand by their veteran leader and ruled out the
possibility to change candidate in the run-up to the September
ballot.
</P>
<P>
Describing Kohl as "the triumph card" of his party, CDU General
Secretary Peter Hintze said in an interview with the German ARD
television network that Kohl had not been strong in opinions
polls, but he had won all elections in his 16 years as German
chancellor.
</P>
<P>
Kohl himself today also told reporters that he would continue
to run for a re-election and said he saw "a clear chance" for a
victory in Autumn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
