<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Light Sentence to Drug Offender Annoys Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan on Monday criticized
U.S. anti-drug laws, saying the release of Pakistan Air Force
(PAF) squadron leader Frooq Ahmed Khan, who was caught smuggling
drugs to the United States last year, would "practically encourage
criminals."
</P>
<P>
"It is ironical that while the U.S. justifiably makes such an
issue of drug trafficking, yet the individuals involved in this
heinous crimes are not given exemplary and deterring punishment,"
a Foreign Office spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman expressed surprise and dismay that the convicted
drug smuggler Farooq was given an extremely light sentence. "Apart
from causing a serious setback to our fight against drug
trafficking, such examples send wrong signals and practically
encourage criminals," he added.
</P>
<P>
Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) agents arrested Farooq in
New York on April 9 last year after he brought two kilograms of
heroin from Pakistan on a PAF cargo plane. He was released on
February 27 after serving a year in prison.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman pointed out that Pakistan had given two other
persons involved in this case stricter sentences and much longer
prison terms, which indicated the country's resolve against
tolerating such activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Calls for Increased Medical Coop with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Zambia Monday called for increased
medical cooperation with China and asked Beijing to provide
medical equipment to the country.
</P>
<P>
N. L. Magolo, Zambia's deputy permanent secretary of the
Health Ministry, expressed the hope in an interview here with a
group of Chinese photographers, who came to Zambia to cover the
work of the 27 Chinese doctors working in five hospitals in
Lusaka, Livingstone, Kabwe, Luanshya and Ndola.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his appreciation over the performance of the
Chinese doctors and thanked China for its assistance to his
country, a source told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Magolo hoped the assistance will be extended to rural areas of
Zambia because there is growing need for medical service.
</P>
<P>
There is a shortage of medical equipment in Zambia. If China
can bring its equipment to the country, both the Chinese doctors
and their local colleagues can play a greater role in their
service of Zambians, Magolo was quoted as having told the
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Magolo also hoped the exchange of visits by medical
professionals will be increased between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
China started to send its medical team to Zambia 20 years ago
as part of its assistance to the country.
</P>
<P>
In the past 20 years about one million Zambians have been
treated by Chinese doctors.
</P>
<P>
So far 10 teams have worked in the country, with each team
working for two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
