<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Canada Agree on Defense Coop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 2 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and Canada
Monday signed a memorandum of understanding which could culminate
in joint defense industry ventures between them.
</P>
<P>
Once signed, the agreement would seek to promote industrial
cooperation between the two countries in the fields of armaments,
military technology, and production, Defense Minister Joe Modise
said in Pretoria Monday.
</P>
<P>
Modise and his Canadian counterpart Art Eggleton initialed the
document at defense headquarters in Pretoria. They also signed a
technical arrangement.
</P>
<P>
"The memorandum aims to identify ventures related to defense
equipment for possible collaboration between our respective
industries," Modise said.
</P>
<P>
Such agreements were important to South Africa in more than
one respect, Modise said.
</P>
<P>
"As a developing country we are looking to partnership with
friendly countries to facilitate access to cutting-edge
technology, long-term investments, joint ventures and new
markets," he noted.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, on the other hand, also offered the world access
to an emerging market in a region with natural wealth and
potential, Modise said.
</P>
<P>
Eggleton's visit to South Africa is the first by a Canadian
defense minister in this century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
