<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Banks Increase Lending Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Facing no immediate stabilization
in Zimbabwe's macro-economic environment, some commercial banks
have increased their minimum lending rates by an average of 1.5
percent in less than three months.
</P>
<P>
Standard Chartered Bank announced in a statement Monday that
it increased its lending rates by 1.5 percent to 35 percent per
annum with effect from March 1.
</P>
<P>
"The rate increases reflect present market conditions and
economic fundamentals," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Stanbic Bank also raised its lending rate by 1.5 percent to
34.5 percent per annum.
</P>
<P>
"This strategy does tie in with the official stance to counter
inflationary pressures in the economy," the bank said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Bankers attributed the latest hikes to the current high cost
of money on the market caused by the shortage of cash created by
the reserve bank to control money supply growth.
</P>
<P>
They held that since Standard Chartered Bank and Stanbic Bank
have raised their lending rates, more could follow suit as the
instability that has been gripping the money market since the end
of last year continues.
</P>
<P>
The latest rise of an average three to four percent in the
lending rates of local banks took place last December in response
to the hiking of the rediscount rate by the reserve bank from
28.5 percent to 31.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The rediscount rate is the rate at which commercial banks
borrow money from the central bank. Its movement upwards or
downwards determines the level of other rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
