<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Varsity Students Start Class Boycott </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Students at the National
University of Science and Technology (NUST) in Bulawayo, Monday
started a five-day class boycott in a bid to force the government
to doubled their grants, Zimbabwe News Agency ZIANA reported.
</P>
<P>
Hopewell Gumbo, president of NUST Students Representative
Council, said the boycott in Bulawayo, Zimbabwe's second biggest
city, would turn into a fully fledged demonstration unless the
government made a firm pledge on the pay-outs by Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The money we are getting from the government which was last
reviewed in 1995 can no longer sustain us because of the
escalating cost of living due to economic problems we are
facing," he said.
</P>
<P>
Gumbo added that it was only a matter of time before students
from other higher education institutions joined the boycott.
</P>
<P>
In Mutare, east Zimbabwe, students from three of the four
higher institutions also started boycotting classes Monday,
demanding an increase in their vocational training loans. They
are also joined by students at Harare Polytechnic.
</P>
<P>
The boycott was peaceful with most students staying in their
halls of residences, while others were studying in lecture rooms
and the library.
</P>
<P>
Charlton Hwende, president of Student Representative Council,
said the boycott would continue until Friday after which the
Zimbabwe National Students Union would meet over the next course
of action.
</P>
<P>
He urged all the students to remain peaceful, saying those who
engaged in violent behavior would be disciplined by the student
body.
</P>
<P>
The students had nothing against the government, but simply
wanted an adjustment in their allowances in view of the
escalating cost of living, he said.
</P>
<P>
"But if the government does not respond during the week then
we cannot rule out the boycott degenerating into a
demonstration," he warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
