<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Trade Unions Give Strike Go Ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Trade Unions, after two
meetings with the government Monday, has again urged a nationwide
stay-away from work Tuesday and Wednesday to press their demands
for the reduction of price increases and taxes.
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General of the Zimbabwe Congress of Trade Unions
(ZCTU) Morgan Tsvangirai told a news conference Monday that
negotiations with Florence Chitauro, Minister of Public Service,
Labor and Social Welfare, had failed after the government
demanded an unconditional withdrawal of the stay-awayi.
</P>
<P>
During the afternoon meeting, the ZCTU leadership informed the
minister that the stay-away will go ahead, adding that it is
ready for serious negotiations at any time.
</P>
<P>
Since no minister had a mandate to negotiate with the ZCTU,
only President Robert Mugabe could resolve the issue, Tsvangirai
said.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, Mugabe is out of the country attending a
meeting of the Southern African Development Community (SADC) in
Maputo, Mozambique. He will return home on Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the ZCTU called for a mass stay-away from work to
press the government for the scrapping of the five percent
development levy and 15 percent tax on pensions as well as the
removal of the 2.5 sales tax increase on goods and services. It
also wants prices of basic goods restored to their pre-July 1997
levels.
</P>
<P>
Nathan Shamuyarira, Minister of Industry and Commerce, said
here Sunday night that drastic and punitive action will be taken
against employers and employees who will take part in the mass
strike.
</P>
<P>
He added that the police and the army will be deployed in the
capital to ensure peace.
</P>
<P>
Economic commentators said Monday the Zimbabwean economy,
already plagued by a host of problems, could be thrown into
further turmoil if the two-day national strike organized by the
ZCTU goes ahead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
