<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Car Phones Pose no Less Hazard than Alcohol: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- A British government funded study
finds that drivers in intense mobile phone conversation while
driving pose no less safety risk than those who drink up to the
legal alcohol limit.
</P>
<P>
The study says that drivers engaged in serious conversations
while driving often result in "considerable distraction" and
demonstrate the same lack of control as those whose alcohol level
was at the maximum of 80 milligrams per 100 milliliters of blood.
</P>
<P>
Citing research results, the study says that holding phone
conversations is significantly more difficult than other tasks
such as changing radio stations and dialing a number is extremely
difficult, the same as trying to read a map while driving.
</P>
<P>
The report points out that when on the phone, drivers feel
pressured to keep up conversation flow even when they would idealy
like to dedicate full concentration on the driving task.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that concern about in-car phones rose last year
after two fatal accidents caused by drivers in mid-conversation
and the government is discussing whether to make use of phones
while driving a specific offense.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
