<HEADLINE> Angola's Former PM Blasts Biased Report on Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Marcolino Moco, executive
secretary of the Community of Portuguese-speaking Countries,
Monday blasted the world's media coverage of Africa, saying it
only reflects the dark side of African countries.
</P>
<P>
Moco, who is also Angola's former prime minister, made the
statement at the opening ceremony of the first Iberian
Journalists' Meeting, the Angola News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to him, due to the shortage of African reporters,
news on Africa are mostly covered by western news agencies, whose
reports are more often than not twisted or simplified.
</P>
<P>
These reports, he said, do not reflect the real picture in the
political, economic and social spheres in Africa, but give a
misleading impression that the daily event in African countries
are merely tribal conflicts, natural disasters and poverty.
</P>
<P>
The official urged African journalists to upgrade their
reporting skills and try to present the world with fair, just and
complete reports on Africa.
</P>
<P>
Portugal has started cooperation with Portuguese-speaking
countries in Africa in jointly setting up radio and television
stations.
</P>
<P>
This is a good experience which embodies the wishes of one of
the western countries to cooperate with African countries, and
its wishes to jointly report on Africa, Moco said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
