<HEADLINE> Israel Urged to Be Realistic on Lebanon Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai said Monday that Israel must be realistic in
face of the fact that it will have to deal with the difficult
situation in south Lebanon for some time.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after visiting Israel's northern border,
Mordechai reiterated that before Israel pulls back its troops,
Lebanese government must prove it is capable of establishing
authority over the entire country and preventing terrorist attacks
against Israel.
</P>
<P>
He said there was not an immediate resolution and it would take
some time before reaching an arrangement, which will deal with the
future of the southern Lebanon residents and the South Lebanon
Army which assists Israeli occupation forces.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai noted that every effort should be made to find a way
of achieving an agreement with Lebanon. He also urged Syria, the
main power to resolve the current standoff in south Lebanon, to
resume peace negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some opposition Labor Party members highlighted the
importance of Syrian role in Lebanon, saying that there is no
possibility of a deal with Lebanon without negotiating with Syria
over the Golan Heights, which Israel seized in the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
Labor leader Ehud Barak said Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
must be ready to talk about the Golan Heights with the Damascus,
who has 40,000 troops in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Another Labor member Ori Ore, former head of Israeli Northern
Command, said that unless Netanyahu starts dealing on the Golan
issue with Syria there will be no solution to the difficult
situation in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a security zone, about 10 percent of
Lebanon's territory, in southern Lebanon in 1985 to prevent
cross-border guerrilla attacks on its northern towns.
</P>
<P>
However, the Israeli presence has been costly - in 1997 alone
more than 100 Israeli soldiers lost their lives in fightings or
accidents in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
There has been strong public appeal in Israel for a unilateral
troop withdrawal from Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
