<HEADLINE> Armed Hutu Militia Free 80 Genocide Suspects in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Reports from Rwanda's central
Gitarama Prefecture, south of the capital Kigali, indicated that
the situation has returned to normal after the attack on
Nyakabanda commune Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Around 2,000 militiamen armed with guns and traditional
weapons stormed the local Nyakabanda prison and released over 80
genocide suspects, Rwanda News Agency said, in a special dispatch
to Xinhua here.
</P>
<P>
"So far, only three suspects have reported back to
authorities," one official from the area was quoted by Rwanda
News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that among the 80 prisoners released were 15
women. The other 300 prisoners detained in other cells were not
attacked, thanks to the intervention of security forces.
</P>
<P>
The assailants are said to have torched the mayor's house and
killed the local assistant-bourgmaster or mayor, whose name has
not been given, and two other people.
</P>
<P>
This brings the number of people killed to 20, including 17
militiamen. There has been no definite death toll of the attack.
</P>
<P>
No number of casualty was given on the government side.
</P>
<P>
Officials in Gitarama also noted that there has been a lot of
damages on property. A number of houses belonging to local
residents were set afire, as well as the building of a local
secondary school. Two vehicles were also burnt down by the
militiamen.
</P>
<P>
One health center was also looted, but the drugs were
recuperated by the army in neighboring Bulinga commune.
</P>
<P>
"The local population is now helping the army to track down
the assailants which have been pursued to their harbor in
southern Gisenyi," Prime Minister Pierre Celestin Rwigama told
reporters Monday afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
