<HEADLINE> British Foreign Office Minister to Visit Southeast Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Office minister
Derek Fatchett, whose country is the current European Union (EU)
president, is to visit Thailand, Malaysia, Indonesia and Singapore
on March 3-5 in a bid to promote Asia-EU cooperation.
</P>
<P>
A British Foreign Office statement issued Monday afternoon said
the British minister "will be traveling to Bangkok, Kuala Lumpur,
Jakatar and Singapore from 3-5 March as a special representative
of the EU presidency as well as an emissary of the Prime Minister
(Tony Blair)."
</P>
<P>
Fatchett, who will be accompanied by Jim Close, Chef de Cabinet
to European Commission President Jacques Santer, is expected to
hold talks on wide-ranging issues with senior government ministers
during his four-country tour.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters early Monday, Fatchett said that he was
"keen to demonstrate that Britain and the rest of Europe continue
to be engaged with Asia. We are strongly committed to assist in
resolving the current economic and financial difficulties in the
region."
</P>
<P>
"I'm also going to be discussing how these important issues
should be taken forward at the ASEM( Asia Europe Summit Meeting)
summit in London from 2-4 April," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
