<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Why MPC Divided Over Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 2 (Xinhua) - The Bank of England's Monetary
Policy Committee (MPC) is again likely to be split on the need for
higher interest rates at this week's crucial meeting ahead of the
Budget on March 17.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is the first since a split on the committee was
made public. The minutes of January's meeting showed that five
members voted for no change on interest rates with three in favor
of an increase.
</P>
<P>
In its Inflation Report, which has to reflect the full range of
views on the committee, it concluded that another rate rise would
probably be needed if the Government were to hit its 2.5 percent
inflation target.
</P>
<P>
Many analysts in the City believe that the MPC is exercised by
the question of whether the economy is turning down and, if so,
how fast.
</P>
<P>
One of the analysts argued: "This is by no means an academic
problem; whether we get yet another interest rate rise depends on
the answer."
</P>
<P>
Economic data since the February meeting suggest that the
domestic economy remains robust but that the manufacturing sector,
and particularly exports, is struggling in the face of lower
demand from Asia and the strength of the pound.
</P>
<P>
Growth figures for the fourth quarter last week showed that
consumer spending grew 1.3 percent in the fourth quarter of 1997
and 4.5 percent over the year as a whole, the strongest growth
since the second quarter of 1989.
</P>
<P>
It is commonly believed here that one big concern within the
MPC is whether wage pressures may be mounting.
</P>
<P>
However, the pay figures, from the Engineering Employers'
Federation (EEF) released Monday showed that settlements in the
three months to the end of January averaged 3.5 percent, a drop
compared with the 3.6 percent average rate recorded in the three
months to December.
</P>
<P>
According to the EEF, the fall in settlements reflects the
intense pressures firms are under as a result of the strength of
sterling.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the ambiguous evidence of Britain's economy,
Bridget Rosewell, Chairman of Business Strategies Ltd, said: "A
2.5 percent anti-inflation target is awfully precise in this
uncertain world and a cautious person would want to under-shoot."
</P>
<P>
"I would rather take the risks on both sides and have a bit of
growth as well," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
