<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environmental Disasters Need Urgent Attention: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Environment
Program (UNEP) Monday stressed the need to tackle environmental
disasters such as the forest fires burning in Indonesia and the
effects of the El Nino phenomenon in the world.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of UNEP's High-level Committee
of Ministers and Officials meeting here, UNEP Executive Director
Klaus Topfer said, "we should join together as a family to
respond to this environmental catastrophe."
</P>
<P>
He told the three-day meeting which opened here Monday that he
would raise the forest fires issue during a visit to U.N.
headquarters next week and at the upcoming meeting of the U.N.
Senior Management Group.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the issue of global freshwater resources, the
UNEP boss noted that there was a need for "early warning systems
to alert nations of potential conflicts over common, shared
resources."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the potential for conflict over the
world's remaining freshwater resources is great as there are a
small number of international agreements to manage water
resources contained in about 300 shared international river
basins around the world.
</P>
<P>
In UNEP, he said, "we should focus our attention toward
forging a regionalized Global Program of Action on Water.
</P>
<P>
"this would be an innovative instrument of disarmament in
hot-spots of water scarcity," he added.
</P>
<P>
The issue of freshwater is high on the Committee's agenda and
participants of the committee meeting will review UNEP's
freshwater strategy.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. General Assembly highlighted the importance of the
freshwater issue at its special session on the environment in
June 1997, and it will be the focus of discussions at the
forthcoming Commission on Sustainable Development meeting in New
York from April 20 to May 1.
</P>
<P>
The High-level Committee of Ministers and Officials was
established by a decision at the nineteenth session of UNEP's
Governing Council held here last year.
</P>
<P>
The committee consists of 36 members elected from among
members of the United Nations and its specialized agencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
