<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nothing New in Israeli Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister Fares
Boueiz Monday refused Israeli proposal to withdraw conditionally
from south Lebanon, saying nothing new in the offer, the official
National News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference, he said that Lebanon will not
negotiate with Israel over the implementation of the United
Nations Security Council Resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
The resolution adopted by the U.N. in 1978 after Israeli first
invasion of Lebanon calls on Israel to end its occupation of
south Lebanon without conditions.
</P>
<P>
At a weekly cabinet meeting on Sunday, Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu expressed his willingness for the second time
in two days to implement the resolution provided security
arrangements are agreed by Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz said that the resolution is very clear and cannot be
negotiated, adding that sitting on negotiating table with Israel
means that Lebanon gives up the resolution.
</P>
<P>
He rejected any direct dialogue between Beirut and Tel Aviv
over the withdrawal, saying that the resolution 425 does not
stipulate security arrangements between Lebanon and Israel, but
arrangement between Israel and U.N. on the one side, and Lebanon
and the U.N. on the other.
</P>
<P>
Israel should inform the U.N. of the date and procedure of its
withdrawal and the U.N. in turn inform Lebanon that Israel will
withdraw. So Lebanon can take necessary steps for the deployment
of its army in the south.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz said that the Israeli proposal is a media ploy, aiming
at minimizing the pressure exerted on the Israeli government from
home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
He also said that France has been cautious when dealing with
the issue, adding even French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine in
Beirut said Israeli's acknowledgment of the resolution is
positive, but conditions attached is not mentioned in the
resolution.
</P>
<P>
Israel has invited France, which has been enjoying good
relations with Lebanon and Syria, for a mediation role on the issue.
</P>
<P>
France has quickly responded to the move in a positive way by
saying it is ready to offer services for any possible negotiation
between Israel and Lebanon or Syria whose Golan Heights is being
occupied by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai is expected to
travel to France on Thursday for discussions with French leaders
on this issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
