<HEADLINE> Khatami: Iran Against Terrorism in Any forms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
Monday assured visiting Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini
that Tehran would fight against terrorism in any forms.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian nation has suffered a lot from assassinations and
terrorism and is now engaged in a battle against this phenomenon,
Khatami was quoted as saying by the Iranian official news agency
IRNA.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting with Dini, Khatami announced his "full
readiness to sincerely contribute to the fight against such an
ugly phenomenon" in a hope to uproot all forms of terrorism,
either state terrorism or terrorist moves by individuals and
groups against each other.
</P>
<P>
Terrorism is one of the concerns of the European Union (EU) on
its relations with Iran, which was labeled by some western
countries as one of the main sponsors of state terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The EU also expressed concern over Iran's stance on weapons of
mass destruction, the Middle East peace process and the death
sentence on British writer Salman Rushdie, who was accused of
insulting the Islamic sanctities in his controversial novel "the
Satanic Verses."
</P>
<P>
"We should not fear difference of opinion because all of us
possess logic and any difference of opinion would be settled
through logic," the Iranian president said, adding that Iran is
strongly against use of violence either by governments against
other nations or by people against other people in order to
advance their objectives.
</P>
<P>
Assassination and violence result only in hatred, which is
devastating, he noted, efforts should be made to uproot such evil
acts from the face of the earth.
</P>
<P>
Khatami also lauded Italy for its "fair and realistic stance"
at the international forums, saying that Italy is considered by
Iran as a country with which Iran can build cooperation and open
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
He said that Tehran and Rome should make use of the
opportunity available to expand bilateral relations in various
fields, adding that he was optimistic about the prospect of
Tehran-Rome relations in view of the two sides' good will.
</P>
<P>
On his part, the Italian foreign minister said that during his
stay in Iran, he witnessed many realities and realized new
approaches in Iran's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
He noted that talks and tolerance were two basic keys to
promoting cooperation and Iran and Italy can play an effective
role in guaranteeing world stability by using the two
above-mentioned factors.
</P>
<P>
Dini also called on President Khatami to persuade Iraq to
respect the accords recently reached with the United Nations and
to strive for realization of peace and tranquility in the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
The Italian foreign minister arrived here last Saturday for an
official visit at the invitation of his Iranian counterpart Kamal
Kharrazi.
</P>
<P>
His visit is the first of its kind since the EU decided to
resume contacts with Iran at the ministerial level last Monday,
which were banned last April after a German court rule accused
Iranian leaders of sponsoring state terrorism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
