<HEADLINE> Rift Valley Fever Kills 4 Tanzanians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The deadly Rift Valley
Fever (RVF) has killed four people in Tanzania, and livestocks in
four districts of the country have been put under quarantine.
</P>
<P>
Daniel Ole Njoolay, Arusha Regional Commissioner, told
reporters Monday that the government and public are making joint
efforts to contain the disease, which causes haemorrhagic
fever-like illness.
</P>
<P>
He said the four who died are from Loliondo and that
investigations are underway to track people who may become
victims of the fever, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Districts under quarantine include Monduli, Ngorongoro,
Simanjiro and Hai where the disease was first detected last
month.
</P>
<P>
Blood samples of both animals and human beings confirmed that
the disease had spread from Kenya, he said.
</P>
<P>
RVF virus is mainly transmitted by mosquitoes. Humans can also
be infected by contact with blood or body fluids from infected
animals which may occur during slaughtering of the animals or
handling aborted foetuses, World Health Organization (WHO)
officials said.
</P>
<P>
However, the risk of human-to-human infection through direct
contact appears to be very low, they said.
</P>
<P>
Teams from WHO have arrived in Kenya to reinforce
international efforts to determine the causes and extent of the
outbreak of the RVF in northeastern Kenya and southern Somalia
where the disease has claimed more than 480 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
