<HEADLINE> EU Grants More Aid for Northern Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission President
Jacques Santer announced in Belfast Monday night an extra 100
million ECU (about 109 million U.S. dollars) aid for Northern
Ireland in a bid to bring permanent peace back to the region.
</P>
<P>
Santer, who is on a two-day visit to Northern Ireland, said the
new donation was a fresh effort to intensify a European Union (EU)
program designed to boost economic cooperation between the north
and south of Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation bloc's Peace and Reconciliation Program
originally provided 300 million ECU (about 309 million dollars) to
help regenerate deprived areas on both sides of the border between
1994 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a donation ceremony in Belfast, Santer paid tribute
to both the British and Irish governments for being "imaginative"
in brokering the Northern Ireland peace process.
</P>
<P>
He also called on all parties concerned in the Norther Ireland
peace talks to resolve their differences through peaceful
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
"The history of the European Union is the story of people who
for centuries were enemies. Yet we have seen how history has
dramatically changed for the better," Santer said.
</P>
<P>
"Perhaps the history of the European Union can provide some
hope and a reference point for the people of Northern Ireland as
you press for peace," he added.  
</P>
