<HEADLINE> SADC Special Session Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The special session of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) ended here Monday
with the decision to reform its regional political, defense and
security institutions.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano,
deputy chairman of SADC, after the meeting at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
A working group was set up to give the exact definition on the
regional defense and security agency, he said, adding the group
which consists of heads of state and government of some SADC
members, will also define the relationship between the agency and
SADC.
</P>
<P>
According to Chissano, the agency is aimed at seeking for
peaceful solutions for various issues which might affect regional
security, and studying on possible cooperation with other regions
in Africa to secure peace on the continent.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also ruled to enhance sanctions on Angola's former
rebel movement, the National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA) because it has not abided by the 1994 Lusaka peace
accord which ends the 19 years of civil war in the country.
</P>
<P>
On the Comoros crisis, which is high on the agenda of the
meeting, the president said, "SADC does not accept any sessionist
activities, we don't want a case like that in Africa."
</P>
<P>
Anjouan, one of the islands of the Comoros, wants to secede
from its motherland and become part of France or independent.
</P>
<P>
The session presided over by South African President Nelson
Mandela, had drawn leaders from fourteen SADC member states.
</P>
</TEXT>
