<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Burundi's President Pierre
Buyoya said in Kinshasa that his country is surviving and
functioning despite a regional economic embargo, the U.N.
humanitarian information unit IRIN reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Buyoya asserted that the trade embargo imposed on his central
African country by regional states to protest his 1996 coup would
disappear after failing to cripple Burundi.
</P>
<P>
"We've made efforts to survive the embargo. We've survived
it," he told Kinshasa television Sunday after meeting President
Laurent Kabila of the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
"Burundi is standing despite 20 months of economic sanctions.
We think this situation will disappear soon," Buyoya added.
</P>
<P>
East and central African leaders decided at a summit in
Kampala last month to uphold sanctions until Burundi made more
progress toward returning to civilian rule.
</P>
<P>
The summit gave Buyoya a rare chance to press his case for the
easing of sanctions. But he stormed out of the Ugandan capital
after he knew the sanctions would remain.
</P>
<P>
Buyoya said his talks with Kabila had been fruitful.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on Burundi radio before his departure, he said the
purpose of the visit was to explore bilateral issues including
security and cooperation. 
