<HEADLINE> Sacked Egyptians Allowed to Return to Qatar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Cairo and Doha have agreed to end
their dispute over the Egyptian workers who have been dismissed by
the Qatari government, the Middle East News Agency reported on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Manpower and Immigration Ahmed el-Amawi
and Qatari Minister of Housing and Civil Services Sheikh Falah Bin
Jassem al-Thani signed an agreement on settling the issue on
Sunday, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
As the first step in carrying out the agreement, Qatar allowed
150 Egyptians, whose contracts have been ended ahead of their
legal time limit, to return to the Gulf emirate.
</P>
<P>
About 25,000 Egyptians are living in Qatar. Since November
1996, hiring Egyptians was banned by the Qatari authorities after
Egypt was alleged to be involved in a failed coup in Doha in
February 1996.
</P>
<P>
The relations between the two Arab states were worsened in
November 1997 when Egypt expressed opposition to the Middle East
and North Africa Economic Conference held in Doha. Since then,
about 160 Egyptians have been fired.
</P>
<P>
Encouraged by Qatar's latest move, Egypt's Trade Union
Federation has decided to freeze a complaint it has filed against
Qatar with the 25th Arab Labor Conference, which started its
proceedings in the southern Egyptian city of Luxor in the day.
</P>
<P>
"The two ministers have discussed means to promote cooperation
between the two sides and enable the Egyptian workers to get their
pay back," Sayyed Rashed, chairman of the federation told
reporters on the fringes of the conference.
</P>
<P>
They have agreed that any other pending problems related to
Egyptian workers in Qatar will be resolved, he added.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also reached another agreement to assess the
prospects of reopening the Qatari job market to Egyptians, the
union chairman said.
</P>
<P>
A thaw seems to be emerging between the two countries as
Egypt has said to attend a meeting of the eight-member Damascus
Declaration Signatory States in Doha this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
