<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
sustained their last week's rally and all stormed to new record
closing highs Monday, boosted by those bullish factors such as a
strong dollar, hopes of steady or lower interest rates, takeover
fever and strong institutional liquidity.
</P>
<P>
Britain's FTSE 100 index of leading shares closed up 53.3
points or 0.92 percent at a new high of 5,820.6, also its third
consecutive record closing high, but below a fresh intra-day peak
of 5,846.9, helped by positive news from the British conglomerate
BTR Plc and a renewed bid for the Energy Group.
</P>
<P>
BTR announced plans to distribute 2 billion pounds (3.3 billion
U.S. dollars) among its shareholders after the sale of its packing
business, reflecting the success of its disposals program.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that shares in the Energy Group climbed 3.5
percent after the U.S. group Texas Utilities launched a
long-awaited 810 pence a share bid.
</P>
<P>
Germany's DAX-30 index also surged ahead, ending at 4,736.74
points, 26.91 points or 0.57 percent higher, encouraged by
advances on other European bourses and fueled by gains for the
dollar.
</P>
<P>
Traders said that the firm bond market was also a driving force
behind the gains, with some scattered corporate news generating
particular interest.
</P>
<P>
Paris has a similar story, with the CAC-40 index also setting a
record close at 3,446.70, up 24.78 points or 0.72 percent,
building on last week's near 5 percent gain and lifted by
spill-over bullishness from Wall Street and robust Asian markets,
but ended below a fresh life high. 
</P>
</TEXT>
