<HEADLINE> Rubin: Mondale's Mission not to Ask Suharto to Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin said on Monday that former Vice President Walter Mondale's
mission to Indonesia was to continue previous talks between U.S.
President Bill Clinton and Indonesian President Suharto, but not
to ask President Suharto to quit.
</P>
<P>
In answering a reporter's question whether Mondale, President
Bill Clinton's special envoy to Indonesia, would suggest that
Suharto should step down, Rubin said: "It's plain and simple:
not true."
</P>
<P>
He said Mondale's mission was to continue previous talks
between Clinton and Suharto "with respect to the political and
economic issues involved in restoring confidence" rather than to
talks about the second tranche of an International Monetary Fund
reform program.
</P>
<P>
"That (a second tranche) is not the purpose of his mission,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said Indonesia needed to follow through on the reforms
and also suggested that a recent policy initiative by Suharto,
dubbed "IMF-plus," had not been discussed with Washington in advance.
</P>
<P>
"I don't know what the idea is," Rubin said. "it's a little
bit hard to analyze something and evaluate and react to it if
you haven't seen it. The key ... with Indonesia, as with any
country with these kinds of problems, is to, on a sustained
basis, stay with an effective reform program."  
</P>
</TEXT>
