<HEADLINE> Mkapa Calls for Coop in Developing Nile River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian president
Benjamin Mkapa today called on the 10 Nile Basin countries to
seal an agreement to exploit the Nile River waters for their
development.
</P>
<P>
In his speech read by Tanzanian Minister for Waters Pius
Ng'wandu, Mkapa told the meeting of representatives from six of
the 10 Nile Basin countries in Tanzania's northern city of
Arusha, that the Nile waters should help foster cooperation
instead of causing conflict among the Basin countries.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa, who is at a Summit of the Southern Africa Development
Community (SADC) in Maputo, Mozambique, said the prominent thing
is to develop a shared vision geared at eradicating poverty,
upgrading conservation and forging harmony in the basin.
</P>
<P>
"We must create a climate of trust among ourselves," Mkapa
said. "We should aim now at achieving real progress moving from
dialogue and planning to implementation."
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian president also appealed for external financial
and technical support for the Nile Basin countries which include
Rwanda, the Democratic Republic of Congo, Burundi, Tanzania,
Kenya, Uganda, Sudan, Eritrea, Ethiopia and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Six ministers in charge of water affairs were present at the
opening session of the sixth meeting of their Council while their
counterparts from Rwanda, Congo (K), Burundi and Eritrea were
expected to join them later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
