<HEADLINE> Clinton's Confidant to Testify on Lewinsky Matter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Vernon Jordan, a confidant of
U.S. President Bill Clinton, is expected to testify Tuesday before
a grand jury investigating an alleged affair between Clinton and
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Jordan said Clinton and Lewinsky assured him there was
no sexual relationship. Jordan said he helped Lewinsky find a job
at the request of Clinton's private secretary, Betty Currie.
</P>
<P>
Lewinsky's attorney, William Ginsburg, told United Press
International that his client approached Jordan for help in early
November, well before she was named as a witness in the Paula
Jones sexual harassment case.
</P>
<P>
UPI quoted Ginsburg as saying he believes Jordan helped
Lewinsky because "he's a nice fellow," not to buy her silence.
</P>
<P>
Asked if it appeared odd that one of Washington's most
influential lawyers, and a friend of the president of the United
States, would meet and speak repeatedly with a former intern,
Ginsburg said, "That statement reflects the `celebrity mentality'
of this country. Just because someone has power, doesn't mean they
change. They can still be nice people," according to the UPI
report.
</P>
<P>
According to tapes recorded covertly by Linda Tripp, Lewinsky
told her that Jordan suggested she deny her relationship with
Clinton. Ginsburg said, "Linda Tripp should be in jail. She's a
sad, sad human being. I firmly believe what she did was illegal,
unethical, and un-American," the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
