<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi: FAO Warns of Impending Famine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 2 (Xinhua) -- An FAO representative in
Bujumbura has warned of impending famine in Burundi, the U.N.
humanitarian information unit IRIN said in a press release here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Famine is here... possibly to stay as production has dropped
nationwide by more than 20 percent compared to normal years," FAO
official Joseph Tchikaya was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Tchikaya said if there was no supplementary food aid,
malnutrition could intensify and many people risked death.
</P>
<P>
East and Central African states clamped a trade embargo on
Burundi in August, 1996 to protest a coup led by Pierre Buyoya,
and leaders of these states decided at a summit in Kampala last
month to uphold sanctions until Burundi made more progress toward
returning to civilian rule.
</P>
<P>
A statement released after the summit said the embargo, aimed
at cutting off vital oil imports, and exports of Burundi's hard
currency-earning tea and coffee crops, would remain in place
until Burundi improved internal conditions.
</P>
<P>
The conditions include beginning talks with Hutu opposition
groups within and outside Burundi, stopping political trials
until peace talks are under way, restoring security so that
internally displaced people can return home, and freeing
political prisoners held without charge.
</P>
<P>
Burundi Foreign Minister Luc Rukingama Friday appealed for
aid to help make up a shortfall of 300,000 tons of beans, rice
and bananas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
