<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Urged to Ignore Call for Weakening it </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian former President
Mwalimu Julius K. Nyerere Monday urged African countries to
ignore the call emanating from the north for the weakening of
African states.
</P>
<P>
In his keynote address to the Conference on Governance in
Africa which opened here Monday morning, Nyerere said, "Our
states are so weak and anemic already that it would almost amount
to a crime to weaken them further."
</P>
<P>
"One result of weakening the state can be observed in Somalia.
There are many potential Somalias in Africa if we heed the
northern call to weaken the state," he warned.
</P>
<P>
"We have a duty to strengthen the African states almost in
every respect you can think of. One of the objectives of
improving the governance of our countries is to strengthen the
African state and thus enable it to serve the people of Africa
better," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
According to Nyerere, the key to a government's effectiveness
and its ability to lead the nation lies in a combination of its
closeness to its people, its responsiveness to their needs and
demands, its ability to coordinate, and the efficiency of the
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere referred to the criteria for a nation being defined as
"good governance" by the north as a tool for neo-colonialism,
which includes the so-called multi-party systems of democracy,
economies based on the principle of private ownership, and of
international free trade and a good record of human rights.
</P>
<P>
He believed that Africans need to improve governance
everywhere in Africa in order to enable African people to build
real freedom and real development for themselves and their
countries.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that African states, individually and in cooperation
with one another, can move toward "good governance" step by step
and in an ordered fashion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
