<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadia's Economy Grows 3.8 Percent Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Canada's real gross domestic
product (GDP) grew 3.8 percent in 1997, its best performance since
1994 and second best this decade, Statistics Canada reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Final domestic demand jumped 4.4 percent, as consumer spending
and business investment were bolstered by low interest rates, low
inflation and brighter job and business prospects, the statistics
agency said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, personal expenditure on consumer goods and services
advanced 3.9 percent, led by an 11.9 percent increase in spending
on durable goods.
</P>
<P>
"Low interest rates and robust sales of new dwellings,
especially single family homes, spurred purchases of big-ticket
items such as furniture, household appliances and motor vehicles,"
the agency said.
</P>
<P>
While Canada's personal income was up slightly for the year,
the personal saving rate fell to a low of 1.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Individual Canadians have also become net borrowers, when
traditionally the personal sector has been a net lender to the
rest of the economy, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, corporation profits rebounded 17.3 percent,
returning to the double-digit gains seen between 1993 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
With the torrid pace of investment, the country's corporate
sector returned to its more traditional position of net borrower
from the rest of the economy in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Canada's surplus on goods and services trade fell to
15.1 billion Canadian dollars (10.5 billion U.S. dollars), less
than half its 1996 level.
</P>
<P>
Its exports of goods and services were up 8.6 percent, while
its import jumped 13.4 percent, the biggest increase since 1988.
</P>
</TEXT>
