<HEADLINE> S. Korean President Unveils List of Cabinet Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 3 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Dae-jung
Tuesday unveiled a delayed lineup of 17 cabinet members amid the
country's financial crisis and political instability.
</P>
<P>
Kim Jong-pil, honorary chairman of the United Liberal Democrats
(ULD), was named as acting prime minister after the National
Assembly, or parliament, failed to vote over his nomination as
prime minister Monday.
</P>
<P>
President Kim, whose administration has been without a cabinet
for a week due to the partisan dispute over Kim Jong-pil, named
the 17 ministers at the recommendation of outgoing Prime Minister
Koh Kun in an apparent attempt to minimize challenge to his moves
currently being shrouded in legal disputes.
</P>
<P>
Lee Kyu-sung, a professor of Kunyang University and former
finance minister in Roh Tae-woo's government, was named as finance
and economy minister while Park Chung-soo, a lawmaker of the
ruling National Congress for New Politics (NCNP), as foreign
affairs and trade minister.
</P>
<P>
Kang In-duck, a former intelligence official and head of the
Institute for East Asian Studies, was named as national
unification minister while Cheon Yong-taek of the NCNP, a retired
general, as defense minister. Both are a surprise for the public.
</P>
<P>
Hahn Seung-hun, a lawyer, was designated as acting chairman of
the Board of Audit and Inspection.
</P>
<P>
The new cabinet is mainly dominated by politicians as it
includes seven former and incumbent legislators from the NCNP and
five from its coalition partner, the ULD.
</P>
<P>
Besides the retention of Labor Minister Lee Ki-ho of the
previous government, the cabinet list also included a few more
surprises.
</P>
<P>
Those recruited from outside the political community included
Information and Communication Minister Bae Soon-hoon, a top
executive of Daewoo Business Group, and Agriculture and Forestry
Minister Kim Sung-hoon, a professor of the Chungang University.
</P>
<P>
Former and incumbent NCNP lawmakers commissioned as cabinet
members are Park Sang-cheon at the Ministry of Justice, Kim
Jung-kil at the Ministry of Government Administration and Local
Autonomy and Lee Hae-chan at the Education Ministry, Park
Tae-young at the Ministry of Industry and Energy and Shin Nak-yun
at the Ministry of Culture and Tourism.
</P>
<P>
Kang Chang-hee, secretary general of the ULD who headed the
list of five party members joining the Kim Dae-jung administration
under a power-sharing accord reached last December for winning the
presidential race, was named as science and technology minister.
</P>
<P>
Other ULD cabinet members are Kim Sun-kil at the Ministry of
Maritime Affairs and Fisheries, Choi Jae-wook at the Ministry of
Environment, Joo Yang-ja at the Ministry of Heath and Welfare and
Lee Jung-moo at the Ministry of Construction and Transportation.
</P>
<P>
Shin and Joo are the only female appointees, falling short of
the president's promise to give 20 percent of cabinet posts to
women.
</P>
<P>
Presidential spokesman Park Jie-won said Tuesday that vice
ministerial appointments, including the new director of the Agency
for National Security Planning, would be made public later this
week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
