<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Deputies on Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong deputies to the Ninth
National People's Congress (NPC) shared the view that Hong Kong
has experienced a stable economic and social development since its
return to the embrace of the motherland on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to Deputy Chan Wing-kee, a Hong Kong industrialist,
the majority of Hong Kong residents feel no change in the social
system and the way of life in Hong Kong except the transfer of
power and a change of flags since July 1, 1997 and except the fact
that Hong Kong affairs are now managed by Hong Kong people.
</P>
<P>
With what it has done, the central government has demonstrated
that it has strictly implemented the principles of "one country,
two systems," "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong" and a high
degree of autonomy for Hong Kong, he said.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR) has stood the test of Asian financial crisis proves that
Hong Kong people, who are working as masters of their own house,
can run their own affairs well.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Kan Fook-yee, a member of the Provisional Legislative
Council, said that a growing number of Hong Kong people who
earlier emigrated elsewhere have been returning to Hong Kong since
its return to the motherland, demonstrating people's growing
confidence in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Developments in Hong Kong in the past eight months testify to
the correctness of the "one country, two systems" policy and Hong
Kong people have full confidence in the future of Hong Kong, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Tam Wai-chu, deputy leader of the Hong Kong delegation,
said all principal officials of Hong Kong's previous government
have continued to serve the HKSAR after the transfer of power. The
HKSAR is operating well, the Court of Final Appeal has been
established smoothly and the Provisional Legislative Council has
done a great deal of legislative work necessary for the normal
operation of the HKSAR, she said.
</P>
<P>
The deputies are here to attend the first session of the Ninth
NPC, which is scheduled to begin on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
