<HEADLINE> News Feature: Cause of CPPCC Has Worthy Successors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- New faces make up half the
participants in the First Session of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC),
whereas fewer grey-haired were seen in the Great Hall of the
People, where the First Session of the Ninth CPPCC National
Committee was held today.
</P>
<P>
A reporter, who has covered the CPPCC sessions on a number of
occasions, said it is very hard to find old acquaintances for
interviews as there are too many new comers."
</P>
<P>
Yang Zhengmin, a reputed member of the CPPCC National Committee
who has witnessed the development of the CPPCC for half a century,
chatted delightly with some CPPCC members of his age in the East
Lounge of the Great Hall before the session began. Seeing one
after another young CPPCC members passing by, he was pleased at the
replacement of the olderly by younger members, which show that
the cause of the CPPCC has a contingent of successors.
</P>
<P>
A drastic rise in the recruitment of young CPPCC members has
reduced the average age of the Ninth CPPCC National Committee by
about two years.
</P>
<P>
The current CPPCC session included over 40 entrepreneurs from
the non-public sectors, some 20 more than in the preceding
session. This demonstrates that the non-public sector has been
playing a more important role in the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Experts, rather than film and TV stars, are news-makers of the
current session. a crowd of reporters in the eastern lounge, are
seen looking for and chasing scholars and experts majored in the
fields of economy, science and technology and education for
possible interviews.
</P>
<P>
Take Gao Shangquan, a noted economist and vice-president of the
China Society for restructuring economy. He responded with
meticulous and measured words to a succession of questions raised
by reporters from Hong Kong in the Eastern Lounge.  
</P>
</TEXT>
