<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, Turkmenistan Call for Caspian Legal Regime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Turkmenistan on Tuesday
called for expedition of the process of formulating a Caspian Sea
legal regime to settle disputes among littoral states, according
to Iran's official news agency.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi met with his Turkmen
counterpart Boris Shikhmuradov, who arrived here Monday on an
official visit, to focus on the issue of Caspian.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said only a sole legal regime acceptable to all
Caspian states could secure the desirable and legitimate
exploitation of resources as well as shipping in the sea.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers believed any unilateral exploitation of the
sea resources was against the interests of all states bordering
the world's largest lake, and vowed to continue bilateral
consultations over the issue.
</P>
<P>
Energy Experts said the Caspian has proven reserves of up to 16
billion barrels of oil and 8.3 trillion cubic meters of natural
gas. Disputes over the rights to exploit the wealth have erupted
among the five littoral states - Iran, Azerbaijan, Russia,
Turkmenistan and Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
Iran, which opposed unilateral actions, has proposed setting up
a legal regime governing the Caspian. The legal regime, it said,
should be based on the Treaty of Amity concluded between Iran and
Russia in 1921 and the Commerce and Navigation Agreement it struck
with the former Soviet Union in 1940.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi visited Moscow last week to coordinate stance on the
Caspian issue with Russian officials. But there were no details of
the result of his mission.
</P>
<P>
Turkmenistan, which has vast gas reserves in its huge basin
below the desert, is probing to the possibility of lay a pipeline
through Iran to export gas. This topic was taken up by the two
ministers in their talks Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
They also reviewed further expansion of bilateral and regional
cooperation in political, economic, trade and oil fields, and
discussed the preparation for the forthcoming visit of Turkmen
President Saparmurad Niyazov to Tehran. However, no exact date was
given for the visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
