<HEADLINE> 3 Planes Land in Baghdad with Relief Supplies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Two planes from the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) and one from Morocco carrying relief supplies for
the Iraqi people arrived at the Saddam International Airport
Tuesday, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The two UAE planes carried 80 tonnes of medicines and medical
appliances as a donation from the UAE Red Crescent Society to the
Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Head of the UAE delegation Mohammed al-Mansouri said at the
airport that they wanted to express solidarity with the Iraqi
people who have been suffering from the "unjust" embargo imposed
on them for more than seven years.
</P>
<P>
The Moroccan plane carried 10 tonnes of medicines and foodstuff
provided by the Union Marocaine du Travail (Moroccan Labor Union).
</P>
<P>
In press statements upon his arrival at the airport, Ahmed
Hossaini, member of the executive bureau of the union, called on
the Arab governments and people to stand by Iraq against both the
U.N. embargo and the U.S. aggressive threats.
</P>
<P>
The three flights were approved by the U.N. Sanctions Committee
on Iraq, according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under U.N. sanctions since its invasion of Kuwait
in 1990. The embargo, which barred the country from exporting oil,
can not be lifted unless U.N. weapons experts verify that Iraq has
been disarmed of weapons of mass destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
