<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are the business
briefs from countries of the Middle East:
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- A French bank will help Lebanon to issue 2 billion
U.S. dollars of treasury bonds in Europe, the local Daily Star
newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Michel Franscois, president of the French Bank of Paribas, made
the offer on Sunday when he met with Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri.
</P>
<P>
The French bank issued for Lebanon 300 million dollars bond in
Europe in 1995 and 100 million dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The Iranian Economic Council headed by President
Mohammad Khatami has agreed Iran Air, the national carrier, to
lease six aircraft to increase its transportation capacity, the
Iranian official news agency IRNA reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The Iranian government has started to offer 750
million U.S. dollars in government securities to boost the budget
for the new fiscal year beginning from March 21.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Iran announced Monday the duration of the
National Partnership Securities is three years with an initial
interest rate of 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries
has expected the world demand for oil will amount to 75.6 million
barrels per day in the year and that the oil supply will reach
75.7 million barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- A surge of demand has raised the exchange rate of the
Iraqi dinar against the Jordanian dinar after the end of the
standoff over arms inspections between Iraq and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, 550 Jordanian dinars can buy 1 million Iraqi
dinars, 80 Jordanian dinars more than the exchange rate before the
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The budget deficit of the six Gulf Cooperation
Council states is expected to rise by 59 percent in this fiscal
year due to the oil price slump, according to a study issued by
the Emirates Industrial Bank of the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
The study showed that the gap between income and spending would
widen if the oil price continue to fall.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit of the GCC states last year stood at 7.8
billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
