<HEADLINE> Shanghai Working on Fairer Judiciary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai is trying to
establish a judiciary that will ensure fairer law-enforcement over
the next five years.
</P>
<P>
A recent conference of the presidents of courts in Shanghai
decided that a higher quality group of clean, honest, and
proficient judges will be found in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, Shanghai courts have heard 707,538
cases, double the figure of the previous five years.
</P>
<P>
Hu Ruibang, president of the Shanghai Higher People's Court,
has said that Shanghai courts will continue their campaign against
criminal activities, with priority being given to such major cases
as crimes of violence, drug trafficking, firearm thefts, and
criminal gangs.
</P>
<P>
He said that the city's judiciary will come down hard on cases
of bribery, especially those involving Party and government
officials, to safeguard Shanghai's economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
