<HEADLINE> No Progress Made in Israeli-Palestinian Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Cabinet Secretary Danny
Naveh and Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb Erekat met here
Tuesday to narrow the gaps between the two sides in the peace
talks, but no progress was made.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, Naveh and Erekat discussed the opening
of a safe passage between the Gaza Strip and the West Bank,
Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Erakat said after the meeting that Israeli and Palestinian
negotiation subcommittees will meet again next week to discuss
the outstanding aspects of the interim accord.
</P>
<P>
This was the second meeting between Naveh and Erekat in two
days. They also met Monday night in the residence of the
U.S. ambassador in Israel, and ended their talks inconclusively.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have been stalled during the
recent Gulf crisis in which Iraq rejected unfettered arms
inspections by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
But the United States, the main mediator in the Middle East
peace process, has indicated that it will not immediately
present Israel and Palestinians with its own proposals for moving
the peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
Local daily Haaretz quoted a senior U.S. official as saying
that the U.S. will wait a while to give the two sides time to
hold direct talks and solve their problems. 
</P>
