<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North China's Quake-Stricken County Recovering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Zhangbei County, 400 km north of
Beijing, is fast rebuilding itself after being hit by a
magnitude-6.2 earthquake last January. More than 40,000 homeless
people from 16,000 households are expected to move into new homes
by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
According to Luo Quanzhong, a deputy to the Ninth National
People's Congress (NPC) who comes from the county and is here to
attend the NPC's first session, a total of 39,500 houses with a
combined floor space of 684,000 square meters will be built in the
county before the end of the year. Most damaged houses will be
repaired before the year end, too, he said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1999, all the 130,000 earthquake-stricken people
in the county will have their houses repaired or rebuilt, he said.
</P>
<P>
Luo said most of the funds for reconstruction are coming from
the government, with quake-stricken people bearing part of the
cost in accordance with their financial capabilities.
</P>
<P>
By now, all roads, telecom facilities, power supply and
irrigation facilities in the county's stricken area have been
repaired. The four hospitals in the county town have resumed
operation. All the 397 primary and middle schools in the most
seriously hit towns and townships will open for classes on March 5
as scheduled, he said.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake, which hit Zhangbei and other three counties on
January 10, claimed 49 lives and injured 470,000 people. Total
damages caused by the quake amount to 2.4 billion yuan and those
in Zhangbei reach 1.5 billion yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
