<HEADLINE> Australia's Current Account Deficit Rises 22 Pct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Australia's current account
deficit rose by 22 percent in the last three months of 1997 to
5.736 billion Australian dollars (3.87 billion U.S. dollars),
official figures released Tuesday showed.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS)
also showed Australia's foreign debts in 1997 rose to 222.291
billion Australian dollars (151.15 billion U.S. dollars), up 0.2
percent from the previous quarterly survey.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the current account deficit was attributed to a
turnaround in Australia's trade position from a surplus to a
deficit due to increases in merchandise imports and lower gold
exports during the quarter.
</P>
<P>
But the ABS pointed out that the December quarter's lower gold
exports followed the final installment of a Reserve Bank gold
sell-off in the previous quarter, which saw a 4.7 billion
Australian dollar (3.2 billion U.S. dollars) current account
deficit.
</P>
<P>
Other economic indicators released by the ABS showed a strong
increase in retail trade in January as shoppers took advantage of
the post-Christmas sales.
</P>
<P>
Retail turnover rose 2.1 percent in January compared with the
previous month, and was 5.3 percent higher than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Department stores recorded the largest rise in retail sales
during the month, with turnover climbing 6.3 percent over
December.
</P>
<P>
The total number of residential buildings approved in Australia
slipped back 1.5 percent in January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
