<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning Province to Construct High-Tech Research Centers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning Province, an old
industrial center in northeast China, will build four major
high-tech research centers in an effort to revitalize traditional
industries, according to provincial officials.
</P>
<P>
Sources with the provincial commission of science and
technology said that the province will encourage scientific
research institutes and colleges of higher learning in the
province to cooperate extensively with local enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning now has one-tenth of China's state-owned large and
medium-sized enterprises. It gradually lagged behind after its
heyday in the 1950s into the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
The market share rate of high-tech products manufactured by
Liaoning companies is comparatively low, while the quality of some
locally produced commodities is not high. Rough-finished and
primary products make up 60 percent of the total shipped from
Liaoning to other parts of the country, according to the Liaoning
Provincial Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
In setting goals for upgrading this old industrial base,
provincial authorities have put forward a principle of advancing
technology-oriented industries, and using technology to improve
traditional industries and processing primary products.
</P>
<P>
The four high-tech research centers will be the North China New
Materials Research and Development Center, the Liaoning
Information Technology and Development Center, the Liaoning
Advanced Manufacturing Technology Research and Development Center,
and the Liaoning Bio-Engineering Research and Development Center.
</P>
<P>
The province is home to 25 state and provincial engineering
technology centers involving computer software, automation,
numerical control and robots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kim Jong-pil Appointed S.Korean Acting Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 3 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Dae-jung
appointed a controversial figure as acting prime minister Tuesday,
a day after the parliament failed to vote over the same person's
nomination as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
"I had no choice but to urgently appoint Kim Jong-pil as acting
prime minister," President Kim told his first press conference
since he took office last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The vote by the National Assembly, or parliament, on the
nomination was suspended Monday when lawmakers from the ruling
coalition of the National Congress, New Politics and United
Liberal Democrats physically clashed with those from the
opposition Grand National Party (GNP).
</P>
<P>
Members of the GNP, which occupies 161 seats at the 299-member
parliament against the ruling coalition's 122 seats, collectively
cast "unmarked" vote slips to veto the nomination.
</P>
<P>
The GNP said Kim Jong-pil, who formed an alliance with Kim
Dae-jung to win the presidential election last December, is not
qualified for the second highest position in the administration to
help the nation overcome the deepening financial crisis and steer
the nation into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, the president called for the public's
understanding to his decision, adding that it was inevitable for
him to end the week-long administrative vacuum.
</P>
<P>
Once served as prime minister, the 72-year-old Kim Jong-pil has
been a political heavyweight for nearly 40 years. He was also the
founder of the nation's Central Intelligence Agency after helping
late President Park Chung-hee mastermind the 1961 coup.
</P>
<P>
President Kim's appeal, however, immediately met strong
reaction from the opposition, which threatened to take all
possible countermeasures.
</P>
<P>
"It is illegal for the president to name an acting prime
minister. We will take all legal and political countermeasures,
including asking the court to issue an injunction to suspend the
premiership," GNP President Cho Soon said.
</P>
<P>
A financial crisis starting late last year due to corporate
failures and bad loans of financial institutions is deepening in
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The nation, once the world's 11th largest economic power, has
to restructure its economy under an agreement signed with the
International Monetary Fund for a bailout loan of 57 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country has to return a large part of its
foreign debts of 164 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
