<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Major Parties Vow to Form Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 3 (Xinhua) -- India's major parties vowed
Tuesday to form a new government, although counting of votes from
the general elections is still continuing.
</P>
<P>
The Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) said it would form a
government at the center by taking support of groups and parties
which are opposed to the Congress Party.
</P>
<P>
According to sources of the Election Commission, 422 seats out
of the 535 were declared at 1600 (local time). The BJP and its
allies secured 181 seats while the Congress and its allies got
139. The United Front won 71 seats and others 31.
</P>
<P>
The remaining seats are expected to be declared late Tuesday or
early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We will form the government," said Venkaiah Naidu, BJP general
secretary and spokesman. "What we need is just about 20 more MPs
and there are groups and parties which are committed to
anti-Congressism."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Congress and the main constituents of the
outgoing United Front favored a coalition government of all
secular parties to keep the BJP, labeled "communal forces," and
its allies out of power.
</P>
<P>
Congress General Secretary Ghulam Nabi Azad disclosed on
Tuesday that talks with the United Front on the formation of the
next government had already started, but he declined to give
details.
</P>
<P>
He said the Congress should head the coalition. But the United
Front has said repeatedly that the prime minister post should go
to the party that secures the maximum number of seats in
parliament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
