<HEADLINE> Jordanian King Visits Gulf to Push for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan left here
Tuesday morning on a five-day visit to the United Arab Emirates
(UAE) and Oman to explain his initiative to open dialog between
Iraq and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The king has expressed the hope that such a dialog will help
dispel the deep-rooted antagonism between the Iraq and the
U.S. and achieve long-term stability in the region, semi-official
Jordan Times Tuesday quoted officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hussein paid his visits following the easing of Baghdad's
tension with the United Nations over weapons inspection, during
which the U.S. threatened to use military force against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"Direct dialog between the concerned parties is far better and
more productive than dealing through inspectors, monitors or
following police-like methods," the king said here Sunday during
an interview with Radio Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
"I believe there is a need for dialog to give each party a
chance to offer its views and define its stand," he added.
</P>
<P>
Jordan Times Tuesday quoted Jordanian officials as saying that
the king proposed the initiative for dialog to U.S. President Bill
Clinton during a recent telephone conversation.
</P>
<P>
The idea needs further development and Washington has not
rejected it yet, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The king is also expected to pursue the initiative with
Clinton during an upcoming meeting between them in Washington
around March 15, the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has not made comments about the king's initiative so far.
</P>
<P>
The four-month-long crisis was defused when Iraq struck a deal
with the United Nations on February 23 to averted a U.S.-led
military strike. The deal granted U.N. inspectors unlimited access
to the sites suspected of hiding banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
During the king's visits to UAE, he will meet President Sheikh
Zayed Bin Sultan Al-Nahayan.
</P>
<P>
From there, he is expected to leave for Muscat on Thursday for
talks with Omani Sultan Qaboos Bin Said.
</P>
<P>
The king is accompanied by Prime Minister Abdul Salam Majali,
newly-appointed Chief of Royal Court Fayez Tarawneh as well as
other senior officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
