<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
set out Tuesday for Niger, starting a ten-day tour of central and
western African states to tap fresh markets, the Egyptian Middle
East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
During his seven-leg tour, which will also take him to Senegal,
Cote D'ivoire, Mali, Guinea, Ghana and Chad, Moussa will consult
with his counterparts of these countries on coordinating efforts
to solve African problems.
</P>
<P>
But this trip is "primarily an economic one in nature" which is
aimed at opening fresh markets in central and western Africa for
Egyptian commodities and investment opportunities, Moussa told his
large diplomatic and business accompanying delegation Monday.
</P>
<P>
"This area holds a hope for Egypt," he said at the meeting held
to review arrangements for the trip.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Egyptian Trade Representation Ahmed Khaled Hamdi,
told reporters before departure that Egypt is trying to have an
investment edge on other African countries.
</P>
<P>
"West Africa is a promising market that can absorb Egyptian
exports. And we do want to import cocoa, timber and olive oil," he
said.
</P>
<P>
This trip, Moussa's fourth to the continent in one year, will
witness the signing of a host of accords on trade and economic
cooperation between Egypt and these countries, with key focus on
investment protection and prevention of dual taxation.
</P>
<P>
His past African tours had produced immediate contracts in
pharmaceutical, contracting, agro-business, and the opening of
branches by some Egyptian firms in the southern African states.
</P>
