<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Angolan President Eduardo dos
Santos, in his letter to 10 African leaders at the weekend,
briefed them on the current development and existing problems in
the Angolan peace process, a presidential spokesman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The letters have been presented to presidents of South Africa,
Namibia, Mozambique, Zimbabwe, Botswana, Swaziland, Lesotho,
Mauritius, the Democratic Republic of Congo and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, Dos Santos expressed his concern in his letters
over the failure to fully fulfil all the requirements of the
Lusaka peace agreement by the end of last month as scheduled
because the opposition UNITA's refusal to do so, said the
presidential spokesman Aldemiro Da Conceicao.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan president urged the international community to
join the Angolan government to add pressure on the UNITA for its
cooperation with the United Nations and the government in the
implementation of the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the current situation in Angola is "very
critical" because the UNITA did not act as it promised in the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time for President dos Santos to write to
foreign leaders to enlist their support for the peace process
in Angola. He had written a letter to U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, urging the U.S. to press
the UNITA to observe the peace agreement. 
