<HEADLINE> Building of Sino-U.S. Car Project Goes Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The construction of the Shanghai
GM Co., a Sino-U.S. joint venture, is going smoothly with its
230,000-square-meter industrial buildings nearly complete.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Buick sedans, the main product of the project, are
expected to begin manufacturing by the end of the year. Scaled
production is expected to start in April of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The local content ratio of Shanghai Buicks will begin at 40
percent and reach 80 percent in three years. The project's
annual capacity is designed to top 100,000 units eventually.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai GM Co. and its subsidiary, Pan-Asia Automotive
Technical Center, were launched in January of 1997, with a total
investment of 1.52 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The project, which is located in the Jinqiao Export Processing
Zone in the Pudong New Area, has been made the top priority for
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The project is being jointly funded by the Shanghai Automotive
Industry Corp. and General Motors, with each party holding a 50
percent stake.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, China's largest economic and financial center, is
also the top automotive production center in the
country. Currently, the Shanghai-Volkswagen Automotive Co., a
Sino-German joint venture, leads the country in car-making.
</P>
</TEXT>
