<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shaanxi Auctions State Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The auctioning of some poorly
performing state enterprises in northwest China's Shaanxi Province
has provided more choices to reform the state sector.
</P>
<P>
Twelve small businesses found buyers in last month's auction,
and another 20 have signed contracts to sell property rights
involving 50 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Linwei District of Weinan initiated the activity. A
300-square-meter hall was crowded with nearly 2,000 participants,
including farmers. Farmer Meng Dawei purchased a shop for 101,000
yuan after a competitive round of bidding.
</P>
<P>
Li Zhiguo bought his own factory for 560,000 yuan on behalf of
eight workers. "We were determined to win the auction," Li
said. "We will certainly achieve good results so long as we do our
best, because we have good policies."
</P>
<P>
The district government adopted regulations to guide the
auction, as well as favorable policies to encourage the
effort. One policy allows some net assets of the sold enterprise
to be set aside to any buyer who is willing to accept laid-off
workers.
</P>
<P>
The auction was organized by the provincial Auctioneering
Center. "The whole auction process proved open, fair and just,"
said Hao Yuanxiao, an auctioneer with the center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
