<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> El Nino Continuing to Dominate World Climate, WMO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The weather phenomenon known as El
Nino has passed its peak in some areas like Australia, but its
influence is likely to continue well into May in some other areas.
</P>
<P>
The destructive phenomenon, said the World Meteorological
Organization (WMO) in its special "El Nino Update" released here
Tuesday, dominated climatic conditions in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
Triggered by abnormally warm ocean current, El Nino caused
extreme precipitation and severe storms in certain areas, and
exceptionally dry conditions in others, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Based on current conditions in the tropical Pacific, on
official sea-surface temperature predictions, and on results from
historical studies on El Nino's effects, the WMO forecasts:
</P>
<P>
-- Warm episode conditions are expected to continue through
April and to weaken during May-July. Drier-than-normal conditions
are expected over Indonesia, northern South America and parts of
southern Africa during the next few months.
</P>
<P>
-- Wetter-than-normal conditions should continue in central and
eastern equatorial Pacific, along the coasts of Ecuador and
northern Peru, and over south-eastern South America.
</P>
<P>
-- Increased storminess and wetter-than-normal conditions are
expected to continue over California and the southern third of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
-- Warmer-than-normal conditions will persist over much of
central North America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
