<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Conference of Sister Cities Opens in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The International Conference
of Sister Cities and Municipal Organizations opened here Tuesday
under the shadow of the stalled Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
About 700 delegates from over 50 countries participated in
the three-day event to discuss municipal problems at the turn of
the century, ways to enhance international municipal cooperation
and how to contribute to promoting international friendship and
economic development.
</P>
<P>
Due to the stalemate in the Israeli-Arab peace process, Arab
cities boycotted the conference and the Palestinian National
Authority only sent three delegates to attend the gathering.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the conference, Israeli President Ezer Weizman
extended warm welcome to the Palestinian delegates, while
expressing the hope that in the future Israeli cities and
Palestinian cities would become "warm neighbors."
</P>
<P>
He added that "I would rather see happy neighbors are better
than hungry neighbors."
</P>
<P>
But Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu opened his speech
with a strong statement that the disputed Jerusalem would remain
the eternal united capital of the Jewish people under Israeli
sovereignty. He, nevertheless, expressed the confidence that
Israel would conclude peace with all Arab neighbors so that
Israeli and Arab cities would become twin cities also.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu stressed the importance of enhancing international
municipal cooperation in the face of an emerging global economy
caused by the drastic changes in modern technology.
</P>
<P>
Eberhard Diepgen, Chairman of International Union of Local
Authorities and Mayor of Cologne of Germany, emphasized the
important role that municipal cooperation has played in promoting
international understanding and exchanges as well as economic
development.
</P>
<P>
He issued a call to Israelis and Palestinians to continue
advancing the peace process on the basis of honoring Oslo
principles and international laws.
</P>
<P>
A strike was observed in the Arab East Jerusalem by
Palestinians to protest Jerusalem Mayor Ehud Olmert's planned tour
of the city with conference participants. Several incidents of
stone-throwing by Palestinians were reported.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference will focus on tackling issues vital to
local governments around the world. Discussion groups will debate
municipal and economic cooperation, youth exchanges, urban
planning and the problems facing metropolitan and capital cities.
</P>
<P>
A seven-member Chinese delegation led by Su Guang, Vice
President of the Chinese People's Association for Friendship with
Foreign Countries, took part in the conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
