<HEADLINE> Export Structure Undergoes Change in North China's Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The export structure of Tianjin
has undergone a significant change, with exports of
electro-mechanical products rapidly replacing that of primary
products as the city's top item.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that exports of electro-mechanical
products totaled 2.28 billion U.S. dollars last year, accounting
for 45.36 percent of Tianjin's total exports of 5.018 billion
U.S. dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
A local official said that exports of electro-mechanical
products have posted marked increases since 1995, with the net
increase rate surpassing 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Exports of electro-mechanical products have also changed from
common machinery to products featuring high-tech and high added
value.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin exports commodities to such countries and regions as
the United States, the European Union, Japan, the Republic of
Korea and Southeast Asian counties.
</P>
<P>
Industry experts say that, the change in Tianjin's export
structure has shown a rapid improvement of industrial and
technological standards in China's coastal areas, and an improved
competitiveness of China-made commodities on the international
market, which has played a positive role in enabling China to
maintain a stable economy amid the financial turmoil now
afflicting Southeast Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
