<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Strengthen Ties With HK: European Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) will
continue to strengthen its partnership with the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) in times of change, a European
official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Willy De Clercq, Belgian Minister of State, told Hong Kong
business community Tuesday: "Notwithstanding the transition of
Hong Kong to China, the current financial crisis in Asia and the
internal tasks for Europe, the EU should seek to play a more
active role in this part of the world and strengthen its
relationship with the SAR, particularly now."
</P>
<P>
In a luncheon speech, entitled "EU-Hong Kong: Key partners for
the future", he highlighted the European interests in the city --
a deep economic involvement, close personal ties and continuing
political interests.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is EU's tenth largest trading partner, and the EU is
Hong Kong's third largest trading partner. Their bilateral trade
has increased by 20 percent annually over the past decade.
Moreover, about 50,000 EU citizens live in Hong Kong, more than
any other cities in Asia.
</P>
<P>
"The depth and breadth of European interests in Hong Kong makes
it inevitable that Hong Kong will continue to be a key partner for
the EU in Asia," said De Clercq, also chairman of the Committee on
Legal Affairs and Citizen's right of the European parliament.
</P>
<P>
On the impact of the Asian financial crisis on Hong Kong, the
European official said that Hong Kong stood firm and was able to
keep its competitiveness though the economy was not left
unaffected. "Nevertheless, I am optimistic that Hong Kong will
weather the storm," he added.
</P>
<P>
De Clercq noted that business was as usual in Hong Kong after
July 1, 1997. He said: "... this handover has been peaceful and
successful, proving wrong those critics who predicted a doomsday
scenario after this historic transition." 
</P>
</TEXT>
