<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Public Confidence in Banking Eroded in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The public confidence in banking
system in Zambia has been greatly eroded following the collapse
of four banks within a periold of four months, Financial Mail
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The weekly newspaper reported that savings in banks have
drastically declined between December 1997 and February this
year.
</P>
<P>
Total deposits measured in terms of deposit liabilities to the
public declined drastically from 462.108 billion Kwacha (about
308 million U.S. dollars) in December last year to 415.512
billion Kwacha (about 277 million dollars) in February this year.
</P>
<P>
The decline in deposits reduced the commmercial banks' total
liabilities to the public from 487.59 billion Kwacha (about 325
million dollars) to 442.96 billion Kwacha (about 295 million
dollars) in February.
</P>
<P>
To the contrary, foreign currency deposits increased from
137.654 million dolllars to 143.479 million dollars during the
same period, indicating a shift from local currency deposits to a
more secured foreign currency deposits.
</P>
<P>
Analysts have attributed the drastic reduction in deposits to
the collapse of some local commericial banks which created fear
in the nation about the security of their money in remaining
banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
