<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Cameroun Clash in Bakassi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Clashes between Nigerian and
Camerounian soldiers on the oil-rich Bakassi Peninsula has killed
at least 7 Camerounians, just before the International Court of
Justice resumed hearing on the issue Monday at the Hague,
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Reports quoted the British Broadcasting Corporation as saying
that the weekend attack launched by Nigerian soldiers was sudden
and took the Camerounian soldiers off-guard.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, reports from the Hague quoted the head of the
Nigerian delegate, the Minister of Justice and Attorney-General,
Alhaji Abdullahi Ibrahim as asking the international court not to
entertain Cameroun's claim of sovereignty over Bakassi.
</P>
<P>
"If ultimately Cameroun were to succeed in her claim to
Bakassi, many tens of thousands of Nigerian people who have
always been Nigerian and have been governed from Nigeria will
suddenly find themselves and their property transferred to
another country," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Those Nigerians will be evicted from their land and deprived
of their livelihood. We would hope that Cameroun will behave
well, but we have good reason to doubt them," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria and Cameroun have clashed several times over the
ownership of the peninsula since 1994. Cameroun filed the case to
the international court in March 1995.
</P>
<P>
Cameroun is expected to argue its case later this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
