<HEADLINE> Shanghai Displays Archives of Zhou Enlai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A group of precious archives,
documents and photographs recording the late Chinese Premier Zhou
Enlai's work and activities in Shanghai were displayed here today
to commemorate the centennial of Zhou's birth.
</P>
<P>
These include 130 documents, 80 photographs and eight
recordings displayed by the Shanghai Archives for the
first time to give audience access to Zhou's revolutionary
practices in this city.
</P>
<P>
Early in China's democratic revolutionary period, Zhou Enlai
led the Shanghai workers to the third uprising against the
Kuomintang authorities.
</P>
<P>
After the founding of the People's Republic in 1949, Zhou also
demonstrated concerns about Shanghai's economic, cultural and
educational development, and had been to the city more than 40
times for inspections.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Enlai was born on March 5, 1898 and died on January 8,
1976. He served as Chinese premier from 1949 to 1976.  
</P>
</TEXT>
