<HEADLINE> Macedonia: Solve Kosovo Ethnic Conflict Through Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Macedonia hoped to solve the ethnic
conflict in Yugoslavia's autonomous province of Kosovo through
political dialogue, according to report from Skoplj, the capital
of Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
In a statement Monday, Macedonian Foreign Ministry spokesman
expressed Macedonia's deep concern over further development of
the situation in the area.
</P>
<P>
He said Macedonia maintained that the Yugoslav authorities
should hold talks with the entity of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo
-- the only way to solve the current problem.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman added, the possibility of international
intervention could not be ruled out.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Macedonia started to mass troops in its border
areas with Yugoslavia for any emergency.
</P>
<P>
Tension in Kosovo heightened on March 1 after an escalation of
a larger armed conflict between Serbian police and local ethnic
Albanians, during which four policemen and 16 Albanians were
killed with another two policemen injured.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo has a 90 percent ethnic Albanian majority which has been
seeking independence from Yugoslavia since 1981.
</P>
<P>
Violence there has been growing this year following the
non-implementation of an education agreement reached between
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and leader of the ethnic
Albanians, Ibrahim Rugova. 
</P>
