<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Streamline Local Authorities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 3 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is considering
rationalizing 843 local authorities to about 500, and reducing
the country's 11,300 councillors by half in terms of proposed
amendments to local government legislation, local daily Business
Day reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Much of the rationalization is expected to take place in
smaller towns and rural areas, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that about one third of all local authorities
are financially unviable and do not have managerial capacity or
discretionary funds to deliver services at an acceptable level.
</P>
<P>
The white paper, which attempts to address these and other
problems, has been approved by the cabinet and will be made
public soon, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
Chippy Oliver, the Constitutional Affairs Department's local
government deputy director-general, said Monday the white paper
was intended to "leapfrog local government into the 21st
century".
</P>
<P>
There would be a major overhaul of administrative systems,
while consideration would be given to outsourcing and
corporatizing some functions and privatizing noncore businesses.
These included abattoirs and petrol stations owned by local
government.
</P>
<P>
Private and public sector partnerships could be established
for the provision of water, electricity and gas.
</P>
<P>
Oliver said the biggest task was to redemarcate municipal
boundaries. An independent board would oversee this process with
a municipal redemarcation bill scheduled to go before parliament
this month.
</P>
<P>
Metropolitan areas would be largely unaffected, but there
would be significant amalgamation of smaller towns and the
reincorporation of rural areas, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
