<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: SADC Leaders Plan to Resolve Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG,March 3 (Xinhua) -- Heads of state from the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) Monday appointed
three presidents from the grouping to resolve a long-standing
dispute over the running of the region's security affairs.
</P>
<P>
The decision, which ends an impasse of more than six months on
the dispute that threatened to sour relations in the SADC, was
made in Maputo, Mozambique, during a one-day special session of
the regional organization.
</P>
<P>
Namibian President Sam Nujoma, Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano and Malawian President Bakili Muluzi were tasked with
reconciling two proposals aimed at resolving the dispute over the
SADC's political, defense and security sub-committee.
</P>
<P>
The dispute, which came to a head last August, centred on
whether the sub-committee, chaired by Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe, should have its status elevated to the same level as the
SADC itself.
</P>
<P>
If this view -- favored by Mugabe -- prevailed, then the
subcommittee would hold a separate summit and not report to the
SADC's chairman, South African President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
South Africa felt that the subcommittee was a SADC's
institution that should logically report to the SADC chairman.
</P>
<P>
Monday's meeting, also attended by President Laurent Kabila of
the Democratic Republic of Congo, was the first serious attempt
by leaders to resolve the spat which saw Mandela threatening to
quit as the SADC's chairman.
</P>
<P>
South African presidential spokesman Parks Mankahlana told the
press here Monday night that it was inappropriate to outline the
proposals at this stage, but progress was made at Monday's
meeting which he described as constructive.
</P>
<P>
The three-president committee, which was also expected to
discuss the matter with SADC security affairs ministers, would
unveil its finding in two months' time.
</P>
<P>
The subcommittee's activities were suspended in August,
pending the special session of the SADC leaders.
</P>
<P>
SADC was formed in 1992 to coordinate efforts for a common
market by 2000. The regional body is made up of 14 member states,
with a total population of 150 million and a combined gross
domestic product of 170 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Sino-Russian Railway Scheduled to Start Service on July 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Construction of the railway
linking Hunchun of northeast China's Jilin Province and the
Russian city of Mahalino is going on rapidly.
</P>
<P>
Both sides have agreed to start joint international
transportation on July 1, according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
Ding Shicheng, adviser to the United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) and chief planner of the Tumen River project, said
that the operation of the Sino-Russian railway and the completion
of other auxiliary facilities will help form a triangular rail
network along the lower reaches of the Tumen River. This network
will connect China, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea
(DPRK) and Russia and will create a better investment environment
in the region, Ding added.
</P>
<P>
The Tumen River flows along China's border with Russia and
the DPRK. In 1991, the U.N. decided to include the development of
the Tumen River area as one of its priority projects. A global
center for the exchange of materials is planned for the area
within 20 years at a cost of 30 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-Russian border railway is part of the Northeast Asian
trunk transport line supported by the UNDP. The Tumen-Hunchun
section of the Sino-Russian railway has been in temporary use
since June 1996, and rails were laid for the Hunchun-Changlingzi
section, which was connected with the Russian line in October 1996.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
