<HEADLINE> Floods in Southern S. Africa Kill Seven </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Widespread flooding in the
southeastern area of South Africa over the past few days had
claimed at least seven lives by Monday, left hundreds homeless
and cut off many villages and towns.
</P>
<P>
As torrential rains continued to wreak havoc in the Eastern
Cape Province on the southeastern coast Monday, police said they
expected the death toll to rise rapidly as reports from remote
villages came in, The Star reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Four people died in East London, a seaport on the Indian
coast, and three drowned in Umtata, some 220 kilometers northeast
East London, police confirmed Monday. Three others were still
missing.
</P>
<P>
A Red Cross spokesman said more than 200 people in Tsolo and
Libode, adjacent to Umtata, were left stranded as water rose to
ankle level in the homes after Sunday's heavy showers. The rain
were expected to continue.
</P>
<P>
A Red Cross team provided tents and alternative accommodation
to residents in Umtata, where the Umtata River began to swell and
overflow Monday.
</P>
<P>
The team called for urgent help from the government and the
private sector as flood victims appeared set to rise in the
course of the week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
