<HEADLINE> Beijing Stresses Management of Migrant Population </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Beijing will take measures to
manage non-Beijing natives who live and work in the city, a local
government official said.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Fusen, deputy secretary general of the Beijing Municipal
Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC), said that while
stressing management more efforts will also be extended to
providing better services for migrant people.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, who is also the director of the city's committee for
public security comprehensive management, said work will be
focused on providing labor rights protection as well as cultural
and sports facilities for non-Beijing natives and protecting their
legitimate rights.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that, since 1997, Beijing has provided 2.5
million licenses for non-Beijing natives, opened an occupation
center and 232 labor centers for migrant workers.
</P>
<P>
Examinations were provided for migrant pregnant women in
addition to vaccinating more than 80,000 migrant children 7 years
old and under.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are 3 million non-Beijing natives living in
the city with 80 percent engaged in business activities or working
on construction sites.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that the goal of managing the migrant population is
to control their population.
</P>
<P>
Last year, some 300,000 non-Beijing natives were mobilized to
leave the Chinese capital under related laws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
