<HEADLINE> Australia Grants Aid to Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Australia would donate 3.6
million U.S. dollars to Indonesia for drought relief and job
creation, Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer announced
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Australia will provide up to 2.6 million U.S. dollars in
assistance through non-government organizations for drought relief
and employment creation in eastern Indonesia, the foreign minister
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Downer also revealed Australia had intervened on Indonesia's
behalf with the World Bank, which is demanding major economic
reforms in return for bailing out Indonesia's economy.
</P>
<P>
"The Australian government was able to bring together a number
of other key donors, including the World Bank, to discuss food
shortages and the social impacts of the economic difficulties in
Indonesia," he said.
</P>
<P>
The aid announcement followed discussions last week with
Indonesia on how Australia could best help the country through its
economic crisis, Downer said.
</P>
<P>
The Small Activities Scheme, a long-standing grassroots
community development program administered by the Australian
Embassy in Jakarta, will now be used for drought relief and
employment creation and will be increased by about one million
U.S. dollars, he added.
</P>
<P>
The announcement takes Australia's contribution to Indonesia to
5.8 million U.S. dollars since October last year.
</P>
<P>
Australia will also help Indonesia's National Planning Board
develop job creation programs and assist Indonesia to improve the
delivery of government services.
</P>
<P>
The Australian government, which regards Indonesia as one of
the four most important countries to Australia, including the
United States, Japan and China, expressed publicly last month its
concerns for the social and economic situation in its neighboring
Indonesia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
