<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Stronger After Data Flood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
stronger on Tuesday, after a raft of economic data signaled the
domestic economy was chugging along nicely but the external sector
was coming under pressure from Asia.
</P>
<P>
The unit closed at 68.35 U.S. cents, from 68.08 previously.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the data were mostly in line with expectations.
</P>
<P>
"But it may have been interpreted a little better than
expected," said IBJ Australia LTD Foreign Exchange Manager Darrin
Stewart.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) Tuesday released
retail trade and building approvals figures for January and a
further report on the current account deficit for the December
quarter.
</P>
<P>
The ABS said retail sales in January rose a
stronger-than-expected 2.1 percent, in seasonally adjusted terms.
</P>
<P>
January building approvals slid 1.5 percent, but the outcome
was in line with market expectations and came on the back of gains
of 6.7 percent in December and 1.6 percent in November.
</P>
<P>
The current account deficit widened to an as-expected 5.7
billion Australian dollars (3.87 billion U.S. dollars) in the
December quarter of 1997, from a deficit of 4.63 billion
Australian dollars (3.15 billion U.S. dollars) previously.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar was at 85.75 Japanese
yen, from 85.30 and at 1.2414 German marks from 1.2273. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
