<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Station More Forces at Borders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's armed forces are
prepared to station more personnel at the borders to check the
entry of illegal immigrants, Defense Minister Syed Hamid Albar
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The armed forces and police have reached an understanding on
this matter and military posts throughout the country have been
directed to assist police if the need arose, he told reporters
after visiting the demonstration site of the Defense Services Asia
Exhibition and Conference 98 (DSA) here, which will be held from
April 21 to 24.
</P>
<P>
The number of illegal immigrants entering Malaysia was reported
to have increased significantly in the past two months following
the economic downturn in some neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Police statistics show that 3,000 illegal immigrants were
arrested in just the first two weeks of last month compared to
9,000 in the whole of last year.
</P>
<P>
Police Inspector-General Rahim Noor recently ordered an
increase in the number of police personnel involved in checking
the entry of illegal immigrants along the west coast of the
peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, which itself is experiencing an economic downturn due
to the contagion effects of the regional financial crisis, already
has some 2 million foreign workers, half of whom are said illegal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
