<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aziz: Iraq Will Observe Agreement on Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq
Aziz said Tuesday that Iraq will observe the agreement with
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on peacefully ending the crisis
over weapons inspection, Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said in a statement to the INA that Iraq who has put its
signature to the agreement will honor its commitment and respect
U.N. Security Council resolutions concerning the agreement.
</P>
<P>
He was responding to the U.N. Security Council resolution
adopted on Monday that warns Iraq of "severest consequences" if it
again bars U.N. arms inspectors from suspected sites in their
search for weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
In a unanimous vote Monday night, the 15-member U.N. Security
Council adopted the resolution drafted by Britain and Japan,
which declares that "any violation (of the agreement) would have
severest consequences for Iraq."
</P>
<P>
Under the Memorandum of Understanding signed by Annan and Aziz
on February 23, Iraq agreed to grant a U.N special group free,
unconditional and unrestricted access to its presidential palaces.
</P>
<P>
The special group will comprise of senior diplomats appointed
by Annan and arms inspectors drawn from the U.N. Special
Commission on dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction,
known as UNSCOM, and the International Atomic Energy Agency.
</P>
<P>
The resolution adopted Monday does not spell out what the
consequences will be if Iraq violates the agreement on weapons
inspections, but U.S. officials have said any further violation by
Iraq would ensure strong support for military strikes.
</P>
<P>
Aziz criticized the United States for maintaining military
presence in the Gulf region, saying that Iraq was not, is
not and will not be scared by military threats.
</P>
<P>
He also accused the United States of committing crimes of
genocide against Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
However, Aziz said Iraq is ready to engage in "constructive and
civilised" dialogues at different levels with the United States
and Britain.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has destroyed all its weapons of mass destruction, Aziz
said, adding that the U.N. sanctions imposed on it since 1990
should therefore be lifted.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraq hoped to develop relationship with members
of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC), including Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The GCC groups Bahrain, Oman, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, the United
Arab Emirates and Qatar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
