<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Down on Current Account Figures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket,
trading lower Tuesday because of poor current account figures,
recovered some earlier losses but still finished in negative
territory, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries finished 13.5 points down at 2684.4, off its
low of 2671.7. It reached a high of 2697.9.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index was down 4.5 points at 1134.3 while the
all industrials index was down 24.6 points at 4623.6.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 351.31 million shares changing hands,
valued at 1.02 billion Australian dollars (693 million U.S.
dollars). Falls outnumbered rises 663 to 427.
</P>
<P>
Topping turnover was Telstra Corp with 16.38 million shares
changing hands, valued at 60.43 million Australian dollars (41.09
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
BHP fell 10.5 cents to 14.34 Australian dollars while other
major resource companies posted gains on better metal prices,
particularly copper. Rio Tinto added 20 and WMC lifted four cents.
</P>
<P>
Fears of a possible rise in interest rates caused the major
banks to lose ground, with National Australia Bank slipping two
cents, Commonwealth Bank of Australia falling 20, ANZ losing 18.4
and Westpac dropping seven.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, Rupert Murdoch's News Corp, the market
heavyweight, prevented the sharemarket incurring more losses, with
its ordinary shares rising 10.9 cents and its preferred scrip
gaining nine cents.
</P>
<P>
Despite gold bullion breaking the 300 U.S. dollars an ounce
barrier in New York overnight, the gold index closed down 9.9
points at 1123.8, bouncing off a low of 1115.1.
</P>
<P>
Sydney trading in gold bullion closed at 298.35 U.S. dollars an
ounce, down 0.45 from Monday's close. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
