<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rebel Leader Captured in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Philippine government soldiers
captured a top leader of a leftist rebel group who was believed
responsible for the killing of 40 tribesmen in 1989, an army
officer said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Major Danilo Estropia of the Philippine Army said that the
soldiers arrested Amado Payot, 45, secretary of the New People's
Army Front Committee, after wounding him during a brief gunfight
on Monday in a village in North Cotabato province, the southern
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Estropia said Payot was believed behind the strafing on June
29, 1989 of a farming village in Davao del Sur province which
killed 40 tribesmen and seriously wounded eight others.
</P>
<P>
He added that Payot was also believed responsible for a series
of bombings and burnings of cargo trucks and passenger buses,
abductions of businessmen and hostage taking of four foreigners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
