<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Health Ministry Uses New Symbol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A circular pattern composed of a
Hermes' snake stick, olive branches, a picture of the Great Wall
and a map of the People's Republic of China will be used as the
emblem of the Chinese Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
The circular logo will be used in publications, printed matter,
conferences and exhibitions, according to a circular published
here today.
</P>
<P>
The snake stick, a worldwide symbol of medicine, is designed to
be a combination of a snake and an acupuncture needle, which
signifies integration of modern medical science and traditional
Chinese medicine, as well as China's health policy that attaches
equal importance to both approaches, the circular said.
</P>
<P>
The design also means that health-promotion work in China is
part of the world's efforts in this field, officials with the
Ministry of Health said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has allowed its local departments to use the logo
as the symbol of the country's health services only after removing
the emblem's Chinese and English characters that read "Ministry of
Health, PRC." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 08:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish President Leaves for Visit to Spain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman Demirel
said here Tuesday that he will hold talks with Spanish King Juan
Carlos on the regional issues as well as the bilateral relations
during his visit to Spain.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure at the Ankara Esenboga Airport for a
three-day visit to Madrid, Demirel said that his visit will
further promote the political, economic and cultural cooperation
between Turkey and Spain.
</P>
<P>
He will also discuss the expansion of trade with Spanish Prime
Minister Jose Maria Aznar and other high-ranking officials.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish president expressed the hope that Turkey and Spain
should increase investments in the other's country.
</P>
<P>
Turkish sources said that Demirel would urge Spain to help
correct what he called the mistake of the European Union (EU) in
failing to include Turkey in the list of candidates for full EU
membership.
</P>
<P>
The relations between Turkey and EU deteriorated after the last
EU summit in Luxembourg on December 12-13, at which Turkey was
excluded from the list of 11 future member states in EU's
enlargement process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Foreign Exchange Inflows Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's foreign exchange inflows
dropped only to 1.76 million U.S. Dollars in January this year
compared with 53.731 million dollars in December of 1997,
according to statistics of Bank of Zambia available here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But in January 53.496 million dollars was released to service
external debt and to support the foreign exchange market that
experienced high demand leading to continued depreciation of the
country's currency of Kwacha.
</P>
<P>
The donor funding amounted to only 1.676 million dollars while
the remaining came from other non-government sources.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Zambia, the central bank of the country, released 23.6
million dollars onto the foreign exchange market to beef up the
dwindling market so as to save the Kwacha from further
devaluation.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 23.118 million dollars was used to service the
country's external debt which continues to consume the lion's
share of its foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
Last year foreign exchange inflows amounted to only 268.782
million dollars with 140.207 million coming from donors.
</P>
<P>
Outflows last year stood at 267.698 million dollars
constituting a surplus of 1.084 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 267.689 million dollars 146.013 went to service
debt.
</P>
<P>
Receipts from Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM) amounted
to 45.05 million last year and the increased purchase from ZCCM
was led by the shortage of foreign exchange between September and
December compounded by the need to import relief maize.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said unless the situation changes for the better,
Zambians should brace themselves for a more depreciated Kwacha,
which in turn will push up prices of goods and services and
distort the balance of payments position of the country resulting
in higher inflation rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
