<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Companies of Georgia, U.S., Britain Sign Pipeline Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Oil companies from Georgia, the
United States and Britain signed an oil pipeline treaty Monday in
Tbilisi, Capital of Georgia, Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the treaty, signed by the Georgian Gruzneftproduct state
oil company, the U.S. Chevron Overseas and the British Caspian
Trans and Co., reconstruction work on an almost 300-kilometer long
oil pipeline are to be carried out within four months.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline from Khashuri, about 50 kilometers from Tbilisi,
to the Black Sea port of Batumi, will annually carry eight million
tons of oil.
</P>
<P>
The contract also stipulates the construction of the
Khashuri-Alibairamli (Azerbaijan) oil pipeline section in
mid-1999, which will link up the transport system connecting the
Caspian and the Black seas.
</P>
<P>
Describing the pipeline as an Euro-Asian transport corridor,
the U.S. company said at the signing ceremony that the route may
deliver to the wester markets oil from Azerbaijan, Kazakhstan,
Russia's southern regions, as well as from Georgia.
</P>
<P>
Since 1997 Chevron Overseas has been transporting oil from the
Tengiz oil-field in Kazakhstan by railroad across Georgia, the
report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
