<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Airports Safe though Fuel Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 3 (Xinhua) - Aircraft operators and
travelers can rest assured in using the Dar es Salaam and
Kilimanjaro international airports, Tanzanian minister for
Communications and Transport was quoted as saying by media here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
William Kusila has said in a statement that the basic
navigational facilities at the two main airports were in good
order with the serviceability status above 94 percent, and no
aircraft diversion has been recorded over the recent period of
the unusually bad weather linked with the El-Nino phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
"Whilest it is accepted that there are occasional deficiencies
in the provision of airport and air navigation services in the
country," Kusila said, "at no time is the safety of aircraft
operations compromised."
</P>
<P>
He said that a brand new Doppler Very High Frequency Omni
Ranger Measuring Equipment and the new solar-powered
Non-Directional Beacons have been installed at the Kilimanjaro
airport since 1996 while notable improvement has also been made
in the Dar es Salaam airport.
</P>
<P>
Kusila also paid attention to the rising fuel prices, saying
that the government is studying the possibility to reduce them as
requested by aircraft operators.
</P>
<P>
"The government has noted the anxiety of airlines on the
escalating fuel prices and we are trying to solve it," the
minister added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a senior airline official has warned that airline
companies using Tanzania's airports intend to raise prices of
their plane tickets to compensate for the losses incurred after
the government recently hiked price of Jet A-1 fuel by almost 28
percent.
</P>
<P>
Gerwin Mhenga, Chairman of the Board of Airline
Representatives, said that if all other operational costs remain
constant, the hiked price of the fuel would account for 68
percent of the operational costs to airline companies.
</P>
<P>
He said that many foreign airline companies were forced to
refuel in neighboring countries leaving behind only the Air
Tanzania, the Alliance Air, the Precision Air, the British
Airways and the KLM.
</P>
<P>
Mhenga cautioned that the mass exodus of the airline companies
would affect adversely various sectors of Tanzania's economy.
</P>
<P>
He also quoted the airline companies as complaining that the
airports with leaking roofs lack security for their passengers
and cargo, display of flight information, air-conditioners as
well as reliable water and electricity services.  
</P>
</TEXT>
