<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Women Play Increasing Role in Protecting Forests (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A consultant at the Nature Reserve
Management Office at China's Forestry Ministry says that the
Chinese women have become a major labor force in mountain areas
because they know from their daily lives and work that they will
be in great trouble if the forest resources are lost.
</P>
<P>
The role played by women in mountainous areas and the
protection of China's natural resources was the subject of a
Xinhua exclusive interview with the Forestry Ministry's official,
He Pikun, today, five days before International Women's Day.
</P>
<P>
In a mountain village in China's Shennongjia area, a group of
women once staged a protest against the cutting of trees, which
had made a stream that was their main source of drinking water
much muddier. One woman in the area told visitors that the reason
the brook in front of her house was as clean as before was because
there was a national nature reserve up where the brook came from.
</P>
<P>
Women in mountainous areas are now burdened with much of the
farming, gathering of firewood, and getting water, as more and
more men go to nearby or distant cities to look for work and more
income. They are responsible for nearly all their fuel, animal
fodder, and even fertilizer. Their water needs to be saved by the
forests because their soil will erode and their farmland will
disappear if any of the forests are lost, so of course they know
from their own experience that protecting the forests means
protecting their own lives, He explains.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Women Play Increasing Role in Protecting Forests (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Women in mountainous areas have also been the most interested
in afforestation, He says, because of the possibility of extra
income to help supporting their families and pay for children's
schooling by planting trees. One survey he did in Yunnan Province
showed that 80 percent of the tree planters were women.
</P>
<P>
Women in mountainous areas generally have a greater influence
on family decisions than men, and if they want something done,
then it is more likely to happen and be done well, he says, and
suggests that more attention be given to the special role played
by women in mountainous areas in order to better protect the
nation's natural resources.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 800 nature reserves now have pilot projects encouraging
greater participation by women in nature conservation.
</P>
<P>
In the Wuyi Mountain National Nature Reserve in Fujian
Province, one female volunteer nature-protection team has already
been in existence for several years and has proven quite
effective, the official says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
