<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 09:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Students Rally in Iran Turns Violent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Violence occurred Monday afternoon
in a students rally here to protest against the rule of the
Constitutional Guardian Council to reject the qualifications of
several candidates for the Majlis (parliament), injuring several
people.
</P>
<P>
Local daily Iran News reported Tuesday that clashes happened
when members of the Union of Hizbollah Students of Tehran
University (UHSTU) tried to stop the rally arranged by another
student group the Unity Consolidation Office (UCO).
</P>
<P>
The UCO obtained a permit from the Interior Ministry to hold
the gathering after their candidates were rejected by the
Constitutional Guardian Council for the upcoming Majlis
by-elections for five seats.
</P>
<P>
However, the UHSTU also demanded to hold a rally at the same
time and the same place to protest the gathering of the UCO. The
UHSTU's demand was rejected by the Interior Ministry because it
received the UCO's demand one hour earlier than the UHSTU's.
</P>
<P>
Conflicts occurred when the UHSTU members entered the scene
and several people were injured, Iran News said. However,
security personnel did not intervene until UHSTU members tried to
enter the Tehran University campus.
</P>
<P>
The UCO joined the coalition which supported Iranian President
Mohammad Khatami in the May presidential elections last
year. However, the Constitutional Guardian Council denied the
qualification for several main figures from the coalition,
including former minister of heavy industries Behzad Nabavi.
</P>
<P>
Nabavi, a strong supporter of Khatami, also launched strong
protest to the council rule, accusing the rival political factions
of trying to weaken the government of President Khatami.
</P>
<P>
The Majlis by-elections is scheduled to be held on March 13 in
four districts to elect five members for the 270-seat
parliament. Some 227 persons announced to contest the
by-elections.
</P>
<P>
So far the Constitutional Guardian Council, which is
responsible for screening the qualifications of all candidates,
has not announced the result of its work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
