<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Committed to Combat Tax Evasion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Attorney-General Amos Wako
has said that the government would be more tough on tax evaders
to improve revenue collection in the country, according to an
East African Standard report Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Wako as saying on Sunday in the port city of
Mombasa that many rich people still do not pay taxes and traders
at the Mombasa port are notorious tax evaders.
</P>
<P>
"If we collect taxes well, we can stop begging for funds from
the World Bank," stressed the Attorney-General who paid a
courtesy call on Coast Provincial Commissioner Timothy Sirma.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Kenya Revenue Authority (KRA) is out to
eliminate corruption in all its operations, targeting import
business at the port.
</P>
<P>
During the courtesy call, Sirma asked the KRA to streamline
its revenue collection and remittance as a way of ensuring a
strong financial base for the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the country has enough resources to support it
without donors if all the revenue due to the government is
collected and remitted to the Treasury.
</P>
<P>
Wako and KRA officials are in Mombasa for two-day tour of the
Coast Province in the wake of a massive import of sugar into the
East African country.
</P>
<P>
As the high-powered team toured the port, about 10,000 tons of
Brazilian sugar was expected to be discharged at the port of
Mombasa aboard two vessels.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government will once again have to steer the
economy for another half year without the crucial support of the
international donor community following the government failure to
convince the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to resume talks on
its suspended loan package.
</P>
<P>
The IMF mission which concluded a two-week review of Kenya's
economy last week said that "progress has been made in
implementing the measures but further actions are required to
complete the agreed program of measures."
</P>
<P>
Among the key measures agreed between the Kenyan government
and the IMF mission include reducing budget deficit from its
current 3.9 percent to 2.4 percent of the Gross Domestic Product,
more independence for the Kenya Revenue Authority and improved
governance.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held here last Friday, Goodall Gondwe,
Deputy Director of the IMF African Department and leader of the
IMF mission, said that the Kenyan government should institute
measures for the recovery of substantial amounts of customs duty
not paid by sugar importers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
