<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers' Income in Chinese Province Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Per-capita income for
farmers in central China's Hunan Province reached 2,000 yuan for
the first time in 1997.
</P>
<P>
An official from the provincial government said that
per-capita income for farmers in the province was 2,037 yuan last
year, an increase of 8.9 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
As a large agricultural province, Hunan has a leading position
in China in the production of grain, cotton, tea, oil-bearing
crops and ramie.
</P>
<P>
Last year, farmers in Hunan Province grew high-yield rice on
67,000 hectares of land in 10 counties.
</P>
<P>
To help farmers increase their income, the provincial
government provided nearly one billion yuan of poverty-relief
funds in 1997. By the end of 1997, 900,000 poverty-stricken farmers
in the province rose above the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
With the increased income, Hunan farmers improved their
quality of life. Last year, each farmer in the province spent an
average of 1,815 yuan on communications, cultural activities and
services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
