<BODY>
<HEADLINE> eds China, U.S. Launch Experiments with Grass Seeds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Agricultural research institutes
of China and the United States recently launched a turf-seed trial
project here.
</P>
<P>
In the initial two-year period of the China National Turf-seed
Variety Trials project, Chinese and American scientists will
conduct research on 110 types of turf grass seeds offered by 28
U.S. seed companies. The seeds will be planted in 11 trial areas
representing different environments in China.
</P>
<P>
The program -- co-sponsored by Oregon State University, Nanjing
Agricultural University and China Agricultural University -- is
the largest international grass-seed research project in which
Oregon has been involved in the world, according to Oregon
Gov. John Kitzhaber, who was present at Saturday's ceremony.
</P>
<P>
As one of the major grass-seed producers in the United States,
he said, Oregon will provide 121,000 U.S. dollars in financial
support, and technological expertise brought by professors,
researchers and farm-owners.
</P>
<P>
Chinese agronomists say the introduction of the
state-of-the-art turf-grass technology from the United States is
the result of the increasing importance of turf grass for erosion
control and for recreational facilities such as sports grounds and
parks.
</P>
<P>
Oregon is the largest turf-grass seed exporter to China. Last
year, it exported to China 7,000 tons of turf seeds worth five
million U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
