<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Wile card Andre Agassi beat
sixth seed Albert Portas of Spain in a three-set victory on Monday
at the 315,000 U.S. dollars Franklin Templeton tennis Classic in
Scottsdale, the United States.
</P>
<P>
Agassi, the former world number one now ranked 50th, upset the
Spaniard 3-6, 6-1, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
The 27-year-old was the winner of the event in 1993 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
After a dismal season in 1997 when he won none of any
tournament and was ranked as low as 122nd, Agassi vaulted to 49th
this season after beating current top-ranked Pete Sampras three
weeks ago, ending his title drought in almost two years.
</P>
<P>
Agassi, who was on the rising tide of his ups-and-downs trait
in his pro career, has won 12 from his final 15 games.
</P>
<P>
In earlier play, third seed Magnus Norman of Sweden was upset
6-4, 7-6 (8-6), by Carlos Costa of Spain, and seventh-seed Julian
Alonso of Spain was another seed failed to advance, lossing to
Dominik Hrbaty of Slovakia at 6-2, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
The fourth dropping seed was fifth-seed Francisco Clavet of
Spain who was defeated by Jeff Tarango of the United States, 4-6,
7-6 (7-5), 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Only second-seed Albert Costa of Spain survived in the collapse
of seeds when he beat Slava Dosedel of Czech Republic 7-6 (7-5),
6-1.
</P>
<P>
In other matches of the day, Sjeng Schalken of the Netherlands
beat Galo Blanco of Spain, 6-3, 7-6 (7-4), and Nicolas Lapentti of
Ecuador scored a come-back victory over Javier Sanchez of Spain,
3-6, 6-3, 6-2. 
</P>
