<HEADLINE> Iran Condemns Attack on Iranian Reporters in France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran Monday strongly condemned the
attack on two Iranian reporters in France by a group of Jewish
youths, calling on the French government to punish those involved.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official news agency IRNA Tuesday reported that
Iranian Minister of Culture and Islamic Guidance Ataollah
Mohajerani voiced Tehran's condemnation in a letter to French
Minister of Culture and Communication Catherine Trautmann.
</P>
<P>
A group of Jewish youths Friday attacked Abdolreza Mansouri and
Ahmad Moshrefi, reporter and photographer of the Islamic Republic
of Iran Broadcasting (IRIB) in Paris, when they were trying to
cover the trial of the French writer Roger Garaudi.
</P>
<P>
Mohajerani asked Trautmann to spare no effort in arresting and
handing over the involved persons to the French judicial
authorities, saying that the incident against Iranian and Arab
reporters outside the court would create the doubt that there is
no security in France for the foreign reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said he also expects the French government to make efforts
to prevent activities of the extremists which are aimed at
creating disorder in the French society.
</P>
<P>
Garaudi was on trial for his book "Founding Myths of Israeli
Policy" which questioned the reality of the massacre of millions
of Jewish people by the German Nazi forces during the World War
II.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian government and authorities have announced strong
support for Garaudi and asked the French judiciary to reconsider
the case in order to "protect freedom of speech." 
</P>
</TEXT>
