<HEADLINE> DPRK Demand for Fuel from China Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- China's local customs office
neighboring the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) has
asked trading companies to adjust their export strategy to meet
DPRK's increasing demand for fuel resources from China.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent issue of the International Business
Daily, DPRK had imported 134.8 tons of gasoline and 29.5 tons of
diesel oil from China from Jan. 1 to Feb. 11, accounting for 74
percent of its oil imports, as indicated by official statistics.
</P>
<P>
However, DPRK's imports of flour from China in the same period
stood at 30 tons, merely 13.5 percent of its total, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The report stated that food assistance from the United Nations
Food Program and the international community has so far been able
to satisfy DPRK's food demand.
</P>
<P>
However, as the country enters into its lumber harvesting
season, it is seeking more imports of fuel, which is in short
supply. 
</P>
</TEXT>
