<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Announces List of Hazardous Wastes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- China has announced a list of
hazardous wastes, which is the first of its kind in the country.
</P>
<P>
The list -- jointly prepared by the National Environmental
Protection Agency (NEPA), the State Economic and Trade Commission,
the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation and the
Ministry of Public Security -- will go into effect July 1.
</P>
<P>
Hazardous wastes are one of the major causes of serious
pollution. They have great potential for danger, and can cause
persistent pollution to soil, water and air.
</P>
<P>
China produced 640 million tons of industrial waste in 1995, of
which hazardous wastes accounted for 3 percent, according to the
latest statistics.
</P>
<P>
A leading official of NEPA said that the implementation of the
list will provide a basis for the registration and management of
solid wastes and strict enforcement of the country's pollution law
governing solid waste disposal.
</P>
<P>
"It will help to keep close control over hazardous waste," the
official said.
</P>
<P>
The list was drafted according to the Convention on the Control
of Transboundary Movements of Hazardous Wastes and Their Disposal
and covers 47 types of waste.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that the list will be amended with developments in
science and technology.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila, Rebel Negotiators Hold Special Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Peace negotiators of the Philippine
government and the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) are
holding a special meeting Tuesday to assess a five-point agreement
they signed last month, the Philippine News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that the meeting is being held at a university
in Cotabato City, the Southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF deputy chairman for political affairs,
said the two peace panels will center their discussion on the
repositioning of troops in Buldon, Maguindanao province which the
military failed to implement.
</P>
<P>
He added that the reactivation of the Quick Reaction Force will
also be tackled during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Quick Reaction Force, tasked to resolve conflicts between
the military and the MILF, was created by the negotiators last
year, but became inactive when skirmishes between the two forces
recently occurred in Cotabato and Maguindanao provinces.
</P>
<P>
Jaafar, meanwhile, announced that the two panels will again
hold a meeting on March 10 in Sultan Kudarat, Maguindanao, to
formally set the date and venue of their formal talks.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is currently the largest rebel group in the
Philippines. It has been engaged in low-level peace talks with the
government since last year, but the two sides made little progress
toward signing a final peace agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
