<HEADLINE> All Ethnic Minorities Have Representatives in NPC (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- "I was cooking when the head of my
village came to tell me that I had been elected to the National
People's Congress. I felt very nervous then," recalled Ma
Xiangmei, a 23-year-old female farmer from northwest China's Gansu
Province.
</P>
<P>
One of the youngest members of China's new top lawmaking body,
the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC), Ma represents the
Bao'an Nationality, a small ethnic group in China with a
population of only 10,000 people.
</P>
<P>
"I shoulder grave responsibility for my fellow villagers and
people in my county, as well as my ethnic group," she said.
</P>
<P>
The Ninth NPC, which will open its first annual session here on
Thursday, has 428 deputies from China's 55 ethnic minorities,
14.37 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
The Hui ethnic group, China's Moslems, has taken the largest
proportion among the minorities with 67 seats in the new
legislature. It is followed by the Zhuang, Manchu, Mongolian and
Tibetan groups.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-one ethnic minorities, including the Bao'an, have each
contributed one deputy to the Ninth NPC.
</P>
<P>
There are 122 female deputies from various ethnic minorities,
accounting for four percent of the total number of legislators and
18.8 percent of women lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
"The statistics reflect improved political status and the
ability to participate in the running of state affairs of women
from ethnic minorities," commented Mahinur Sasim, vice-chairwoman
of All-China Women's Federation, who has been elected to the NPC
for seven times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
