<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 08:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Wants Mideast Free of Powerful Weapons: Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Washington is working to rid the
Middle East of all weapons of mass destruction, including
Israel's stockpile, but has zeroed in on Iraq because it has used
them before, a U.S. envoy said.
</P>
<P>
David Newton, a career diplomat, is in Beirut as part of a
regional trip to explain the merits of Washington's "diplomacy
with force behind it" policy toward Iraq, local newspaper the
Daily Star reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Newton has met with Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz,
who said Lebanon wants the same pressure to be applied on Israel
to implement international resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"The tough policies on Iraq cannot be justified, because
Israel has its stockpile of weapons of mass destruction and
refuses to endorse the Non-Proliferation Treaty,
</P>
<P>
"It is illogical that the United Nations resolutions continue
to be applied by force against some countries while others are
made to feel they are above international law," Boueiz said.
</P>
<P>
Newton, however, said: "We'd like to eliminate all these
weapons not only from the region, but from the world. Iraq is an
exception because it has used these weapons before."
</P>
<P>
The diplomat, who was called back from retirement during the
crisis to undertake the regional trip on behalf of the U.S. state
department, appeared unconvinced that Iraq will keep the promise
it made to U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan to open all its
facilities to international inspectors searching for banned
weapons.
</P>
<P>
Had it not been for the U.S. "diplomacy with force behind it,"
the secretary general would not have succeeded in bringing Iraq to
agree to inspections," he said, adding that the past experience
with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's promises "is certainly not
encouraging."
</P>
<P>
He said his tour gave him a chance "to explain the American
position of this crisis to the Arab people and important
decision-makers," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
