<HEADLINE> Philippine Banks With High Interest Rates to be Probed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Manila, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Bankers Association of the
Philippines (BAP) said Tuesday that it will investigate banks
imposing excessive prime lending rates to businessmen in South
Cotabato province, the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The "extremely high" interest rates eventually resulted in the
temporary closure of shops and the protest of hundreds of
businessmen in the province.
</P>
<P>
In response to the call of the business group, BAP President
Deogracias Vistan said he will send a team to verify reports that
the banks are slapping more than 40 percent interest on their
loans.
</P>
<P>
He added that the notice to limit lending rates between 21 to
27 percent on loans must have been ignored or neglected by the
banks.
</P>
<P>
The South Cotabato Business Association has urged the Central
Bank to issue an official circular to force banks nationwide to
observe the ceiling on interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, central bank governor Gabriel Singson is set to
confer with the members of the Monetary Board as to whether the
ceiling of five percentage points above the Treasury bills rates
is practical.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, bankers have agreed to reduce their interest rates by
one percentage point every week until the rates fall to levels
that are acceptable to the public. However, the rates still
remained at high levels at present. 
</P>
</TEXT>
