<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiangsu Province Sets Year's Economic Development Goal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province
has set a goal of maintaining double-digit growth in its GDP
(gross domestic product) this year.
</P>
<P>
This goal was approved by the recent Provincial People's
Congress. Provincial officials are determined to chalk up an 11
percent rise in GDP over 1997 plus a 15 percent increase in
fixed-asset investment, a 15 percent rise in foreign trade and a
13 percent increase in service sector trade.
</P>
<P>
According to local officials, the province will continue to
place agriculture at the top of its agenda and work hard to
expand the rural economy.
</P>
<P>
The province's rapid economic growth has benefited from the
steady development of agriculture, especially a steady growth in
grain production, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The province will launch a campaign of increasing per-unit output
of grain, cotton and oil crops by 10 percent in its vast rural
areas and has set a goal for grain output at 34 million tons in
1998 while stabilizing its sown area of grain at 5.8 million
hectares.
</P>
<P>
Provincial officials also will focus on animal husbandry,
aquatic products and horticulture.
</P>
<P>
Improvements in the quality of industrial operations also is
high on the province's priority list as well as maintaining the
rate of development to achieve an average growth rate of 11
percent in industrial added value, sales income and pre-tax profit.
</P>
<P>
Governor Zheng Silin said provincial officials would make
great efforts to foster its new economic powerhouses and establish
its new advantages for economic development by expanding
industrialized farming, electronic information systems,
automobiles, ship-building, petrochemicals, fine chemicals,
biological medicine and real estate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
