<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Multi-Party Cooperation &AMP; Political Consultation System  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The multi-party cooperation and
political consultation system under the leadership of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) is one of China's basic political
systems.
</P>
<P>
China is a multi-party country. Except the CPC, China's ruling
party, the country has eight non-Communist parties. They are the
Revolutionary Committee of the Chinese Kuomintang, the China
Democratic League, the China Democratic National Construction
Association, the China Association for Promoting Democracy, the
Chinese Peasants and Workers Democratic Party, the China Zhi
Gong Party, the Jiu San Society, and the Taiwan Democratic
Self-Government League.
</P>
<P>
Before major decisions concerning the national economy and
people's livelihood are made, the CPC would consult with the
the non-Communist parties and personages without party affiliation
to seek a consensus.
</P>
<P>
Non-Communist parties and non-party personages have
representatives in the National People's Congress and its standing
committee and subcommittees and in people's congresses at various
levels. In this way, they have been able to take an active part in
the running of state affairs and play a supervisory role. They
also recommend non-Communist party members and personages with no
party affiliation for leading posts of governments and judicial
organs at various levels.
</P>
<P>
The multi-party cooperation and political consultation system
under the leadership of the CPC took shape and developed in a long
period of revolution and economic construction. "Long-term
coexistence, mutual supervision, treating each other sincerely and
sharing weal and woe" is a historical summation of CPC's
cooperation with the non-Communist parties as well as a principle
for their mutual cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The CPC is the ruling party in China. The eight non-Communist
parties are political organizations having connections with people
of particular social circles. They are friends of the CPC and are
working together with the latter to advance the socialist cause in
the country. They are parties that take part in the running of
state affairs, which cover the formulation of major state
policies, the election of government leaders, the enactment of
laws and regulations, and law enforcement, among others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Multi-Party Cooperation &AMP; Political Consultation System (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Its main task is to conduct political consultation and
democratic supervision and participate in the discussion and
running of state affairs.
</P>
<P>
Non-Communist party members and non-party personages are
invited to discussions organized by the CPC Central Committee and
CPC committees at various levels.
</P>
<P>
Senior leaders of the CPC Central Committee also invite them to
discussions, at which non-Communist parties and non-party
personages are informed of major policies to be adopted by the
CPC Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
Apart from expressing their views at consultative discussions,
non-Communist parties and personages without party affiliation can
raise their opinions concerning major state policies and
political, economic and cultural developments in written form or
in the presence of leaders of the CPC Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, non-Communist parties have raised more
than 100 proposals of major significance. National supervisory,
procuratorial, auditing and educational departments have set up
supervisory systems of their own and invited non-Communist party
members and non-party personages to offer assistance.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a growing number of members of non-Communist parties
and personages with no party affiliation have been promoted to
leading posts at various levels. Recent statistics show that 8,000
people who are not CPC members hold leading posts in 23 provinces,
five autonomous regions and four centrally-administered
municipalities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
