<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mini Automobiles Gain in Popularity in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese-built mini automobiles
(with engines smaller than 1.0 liter) are expected to perform well
in 1998 in the domestic market after seven years of fast growth in
production and sales.
</P>
<P>
The demand for such vehicles this year is estimated at 520,000
to 550,000, according to the Department of Auto Industry of
China's Ministry of Machine Building Industry.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 497,000 mini automobiles were produced in
1997, up 21.6 percent over 1996. The sales reached 486,000, up
20.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts say the rising individual demand has strongly
promoted the production and sales of mini vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Business records of North Auto Market and Asian Games Village
Auto Market in Beijing reveal individual purchases accounted for
85 percent of mini sales there last year.
</P>
<P>
State regulations on the abandoning, consumption and use of
automobiles that became effective this year embodied government
encouragement for use of automobiles with the small engines.
</P>
<P>
Taxi services in small- and medium-size cities are primarily
using mini vans and cars. In big cities, many mini-van taxis --
called "bread-loaf taxis" because of their shape -- are entering
their obsolescence period.
</P>
<P>
In big-city suburbs and relatively well-off rural areas, an
increasing number of vehicles for agricultural use are being
replaced by pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
Mini autos are becoming increasingly popular with businesses
and government agencies, one of the factors that help enlarge the
minis' market share.
</P>
<P>
However, the production and sales increase of mini vehicles is
unlikely to remain as big as last year. Analysts believe sales
will be affected by a relatively tight financial policy, a further
drop in tariffs and the non-involvement of financial institutions
in auto loans and leases.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
