<HEADLINE> Counting of Votes Continues in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Counting of ballot papers, which
started Monday in 535 constituencies, continues in India Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to Election Commission sources, 224 out of 535 seats
were declared at 7:00 a.m. (local time) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Congress and the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), the two
major national political parties, got 80 and 52 seats
respectively.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that all the 535 seats will be declared late
Tuesday or early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The BJP, the Congress and the United Front, the three main
political forces in the country, have decided to hold meetings
themselves to discuss new strategies after the poll.
</P>
<P>
Poll Surveys and counting trends have shown that no single
party could be able to get a simple majority of the 543 seats in
the 12th Lower House of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Secretary General of the Communist Party of India (Marxist)
(CPI-M) H. S. Surjeet said here Monday evening that the United
Front would make efforts to bring all secular forces together to
prevent the BJP from coming to power at the Center in case of a
hung Parliament. CPI-M is one of the 14-party constituents of the
United Front.
</P>
<P>
"If the BJP and its allies are in a position to form a
government, let them. Otherwise we will try to bring together all
secular forces," he told Doordarshan television here.
</P>
<P>
The BJP, which is expected to emerge as the largest party in
the elections, has already met here and decided to meet again on
March 6 in a bid to muster enough support from small parties to
come to power at the Center.
</P>
<P>
India started its general elections from February 16 and after
three phases of polling on February 16, 22, and 28, the election
process in most of the country's 543 constituencies has been
virtually concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
