<HEADLINE> China Coming In First In Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- China scored average annual
economic growth of 11 percent from 1993 to 1997, or 7.3 percentage
points above the world's annual average for the same period,
according to today's "People's Daily".
</P>
<P>
The paper reported on China's social and economic achievement
for the past year and said China came in 7th in the world in GDP
for 1997, narrowing the gap between it and the major developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
From 1993 to 1996, China stayed in 1st place in cereal grain,
cotton, rapeseed, meat, coal, cloth, cement, and TV output and
ranked high in power, chemical fertilizer, sugar, and crude oil
output. It produced 101 million tons of steel in 1996, bringing it
up to 1st place in the world from No.2 in 1995, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
It did 325 billion U.S. dollars worth of foreign trade in 1997,
putting it in 10th position in the world. It introduced 64 billion
U.S. dollars worth of overseas investment, a 64 percent increase
since 1993, putting it in 2nd place, after the United States.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign exchange reserves stood at 139.9 billion
U.S. dollars y the end of 1997, putting it in 2nd place after
Japan. Its Hong Kong Special Administrative Region ranked 7th in
foreign exchange reserves in 1996 and 3rd in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Over the past year, China earned 12.1 billion U.S. dollars from
overseas tourism, an 18 percent increase from 1996, putting it in
8th place in the world in hard currency earnings from tourism, up
one from the previous year's position. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
