<HEADLINE> Island Province Improves Economic Competitiveness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, March 3 (Xinhua) -- China's largest island province
of Hainan has edged into the country's
top 10 economic competitors, a senior provincial government
official had disclosed recently.
</P>
<P>
The province which is also the country's largest Special
Economic Zone had a gross domestic product (GDP) of 41.8 billion
yuan in 1997, up 6.7 percent over the previous year, lagging
behind most of China's 30-odd provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities. However, its comprehensive economic
competitiveness ranks 10th in China after Shanghai, Beijing,
Guangdong and some other economic powerhouses.
</P>
<P>
Hainan now has basically recovered from an economic slump in
the past few years, brought about by speculative investments in
real estate, securities, finance and catering services.
</P>
<P>
The province has been making the most of its resource-rich
advantages, and found some new economic growth areas. Tropical
agriculture is one example. Last year, the island produced more
than two million tons of fruits and vegetables to become one of
the country's major suppliers.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is another newly emerging industry. Last year Hainan
received nearly eight million visitors, an all-time high, and
collected 100 million U.S. dollars in tourism revenue, up 17
percent over the previous year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
