<HEADLINE> Thai Consumer Price Index Up 8.7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The consumer price index (CPI)
soared 8.7 percent in the last twelve months while the monthly
index jumped 0.7 percent in February, Tuesday's Bangkok Post
reported.
</P>
<P>
Vithun Tulyanond, deputy director of the Business Economics
Department, attributed the jump to the price hikes in food and
beverage sectors.
</P>
<P>
Prices of food and beverage in February increased 1.6 percent
from January and 10.1 percent from those of the same month last
year.
</P>
<P>
Among them, rice, flour and flour-made products saw the
sharpest price rises of 6.9 percent from January and 47.1 percent
from February 1997 due to an overwhelming demand, particularly for
exports.
</P>
<P>
As for non-food items, prices increased 0.3 percent last month
from January and 8.0 percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Some economists predicted that this year's CPI was likely to
reach 14 percent, but someone disagreed.
</P>
<P>
Nateetip Tongkoa-on, director of the Trade and Economic Index
Division, explained that although production costs continued to
increase, most manufacturers tried to maintain selling prices
since they were afraid high prices will stop customers from buying
their products or services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
