<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Opposition to Return to Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The six-month long boycott of
Parliament by the main opposition, the Bangladesh National Party
(BNP), will end by March 8, following an agreement signed between
the ruling Awami (people's) League and the BNP late Monday night.
</P>
<P>
The BNP lawmakers had continued to abstain from attending
Parliament since August 30 last year.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by representatives of both parties
following a four-day negotiation mediated by speaker of the house
Humayun Rasheed Chowdhury, press reports said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ruling party agreed to withdraw before March 31 "all the
politically motivated cases" filed against BNP lawmakers, leaders
and party workers after investigations, the agreement said.
</P>
<P>
"All the 113 BNP MPs shall be inducted in parliamentary
standing committees on 35 ministries," it stated, adding that the
committees earlier constituted by the ruling party would be
reorganized in consultation with the opposition.
</P>
<P>
Radio and television shall perform neutral and ensure proper
coverage of important debates in an unbiased manner, both parties
agreed.
</P>
<P>
The ruling party also agreed to announce within 15 days a venue
for public meetings, according to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the agreement on the opposition's return to
Parliament will play a positive role in stabilizing the situation
of this South Asian country, analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
