<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia, Bosnia Resume Airline Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia and Bosnia resumed
airline flights between Belgrade and Banja Luka Monday, with the
landing of a Yugoslav air transport plane at the Banja Luka
airport.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav Deputy Prime Minister Nikola Sainovich, who headed an
economic delegation and flew to Banja Luka on the first flight,
said the resumption of the flight service emphasized the two
countries' progress and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Bosnian Serb President Biljana Plavsic and Prime Minister
Milorad Dodik welcomed the Yugoslav delegation at the airport. The
officials discussed extending the cooperation between them.
</P>
<P>
The flight is the first between Yugoslavia and Bosnia in six
years. The Yugoslav airline stopped flying to Bosnia in April
1992, following Yugoslavia's division into five separate
countries.
</P>
<P>
Rida Attarashan, spokesman for the International High
Representative's office, said in Sarajevo Monday that the flight
was resumed under an agreement between representatives of Yugoslav
airlines JAT and the Bosnian national air carrier Air Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The Sarajevo-Belgrade and Sarajevo-Pristina flight is expected
to resume soon.
</P>
<P>
Normalization of relations between Yugoslavia and
Bosnia-Herzegovina have not yet been firmly
established. Yugoslavia is demanding that Bosnian leader
Izetbegovic withdraw charges filed in the Hague's International
Tribunal claiming that Yugoslavia was an aggressor. Bosnia has
refused to withdraw the charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
