<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Portugal, Spain Sign Anti-Drug War Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Portugal and Spain signed an
anti-drug treaty here Monday to join hands in combating rampant
drug trafficking activities in their territorial waters.
</P>
<P>
Under the treaty, either of the two countries has the authority
to track, intercept, board and inspect any suspected vessels of
the other country as they sail within its own territorial waters.
</P>
<P>
The exceptions are warships and other government vessels.
</P>
<P>
The treaty also authorizes inspectors to confiscate drugs found
aboard and detain drug trafficking suspects and the ships.
</P>
<P>
Portuguese Justice Minister Jose Vera Jardim and his Spanish
counterpart, Margarita Mariscal De Gante, signed the treaty on
behalf of their respective countries here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The special geographical position of the two countries, with
borders on the Atlantic and the openess to Africa, has provided
convenience for many international drug trafficking group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
