<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Poorest Region to Shake Off Poverty Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua)-- Xihaigu, one of China's poorest
regions in the northwestern Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, is
expected to shake off poverty before the end of this century, a
local official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Home to a large number of Chinese Moslems, Ningxia is one of
the most underdeveloped regions in China, while Xihaigu, a
mountainous area frequented by natural disasters, is the poorest
part of Ningxia.
</P>
<P>
Ma Jinhu, a deputy from Ningxia to the Ninth National People's
Congress, China's new legislature that opens here Thursday, said
that most people in Xihaigu now have adequate food and clothing
thanks to the government assistance.
</P>
<P>
"The proportion of the needy to the total population in Xihaigu
has dropped to the current 25 percent from 70 percent in the
1970s, and the region is expected to bid farewell to poverty
soon," said Ma, commissioner of the Guyuan Prefecture to which the
Xihaigu region belongs.
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1980s, he said, the central government and the
autonomous regional government have spent tens of millions of yuan
each year to help the Xihaigu region to improve local farming
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Despite the constant dry spells that have hit the region in
recent years, the grain output in Xihaigu surged to 678 million
kilograms in 1997, the second highest in history.
</P>
<P>
"We're convinced that Xihaigu will no longer be under the reign
of poverty at the beginning of the next century," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's NPC Active in Diplomatic Exchanges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Eighth National People's
Congress (NPC) has actively expanded friendly exchanges with
foreign parliaments since its establishment five years ago.
</P>
<P>
According to Cheng Xiangqing, director of research in the
General Office under the NPC Standing Committee, the NPC Standing
Committee's foreign exchange constitutes an important part of
China's diplomacy and is playing an irreplaceable role.
</P>
<P>
Up to now the NPC has forged ties with parliaments of
approximately 140 countries, and received more than 150
delegations led by speakers or vice-speakers or organized by
foreign parliamentary organizations over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
The NPC particularly expanded exchanges with the parliaments
of Russia, Japan, major developed countries in Europe and America,
and developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Newt Gingrich, speaker of the US House of
Representatives, and Storm Thurmond, president pro tempore of the
US Senate, visited China at the invitation of the NPC, he noted.
</P>
<P>
During their visits, President Jiang Zemin and other Chinese
leaders conferred with them on Sino-US relations, he said. As a
result, the visits enhanced their mutual understanding of China
and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, heads of the Iraqi National Assembly and
Esthonian parliament visited China.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, delegations led by NPC Chairman Qiao Shi and other
senior legislators visited countries in Asia, including the member
nations of the Association of the Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN),
Latin America, Africa and Europe in the past five years, studying
legislative work in these countries and drawing on the useful
experience for China's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The NPC is a member of some international parliamentary
organizations such as the Inter-Parliamentary Union, Asia-Pacific
Parliamentary Forum, and Asian Forum of Parliamentarians on
Population and Development.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the NPC sponsored the 96th Inter-Parliamentary
Conference in Beijing, which raised China's status in the world
and increased friendly cooperation between China and participating
countries.
</P>
<P>
The exchanges have also helped to promote economic and trade,
cultural, scientific and technological cooperation between China
and other countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
