<HEADLINE> Factory Owners Given Deadline to Sack Illegal Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Factory owners of nine sectors are
given 45 days from March 15 to lay off illegal foreign workers as
part of the country's efforts to solve the soaring unemployment
problem, the English Bangkok Post newspaper said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Labor Minister Trairong Suwannakhiri as
saying that officers from a special subcommittee will begin
inspecting workplaces of the nine sectors from May 1.
</P>
<P>
The nine sectors affected are garments and textile, food, heavy
industries, chemicals, wood, paper and publishing, service,
transportation and commercial sectors.
</P>
<P>
According to Trairong, deputy chairman of the subcommittee to
solve the problem of illegal foreign laborers, the Interior
Ministry will repatriate illegal foreign workers from March 15 to
30.
</P>
<P>
The government put weight on solving the problem of illegal
alien workers by inflicting heavy punishment to employers.
</P>
<P>
Those found to continue hiring foreign workers after the
deadline will face five years' imprisonment and/or a 50,000 baht
(1,150 US dollars) fine for violating the immigration act, and
three years in prison and/or a 60,000 baht (1,380 dollars) fine
for violating a law concerning illegal workers.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is confronted with soaring unemployment after the
economic crisis broke out in July 1997. The number of jobless
people is believed to have exceeded 1 million.
</P>
<P>
The government, therefore, started repatriating illegal foreign
workers, mainly from Laos, Myanmar and Cambodia, to alleviate the
pressure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
