<HEADLINE> Clinton Warns Iraq to Comply with U.N. Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Monday night warned Iraq of severest consequences if it fails to
comply with a new U.N. resolution that demands Baghdad allow
U.N. weapons inspectors access to any suspected sites.
</P>
<P>
"Tonight's unanimous vote by the United Nations Security
Council sends the clearest possible message. Iraq must make good
on its commitment to give the international weapons inspectors
immediate, unconditional and unrestricted access to any suspected
sites, any place, any time," Clinton said in a statement read by a
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's statement came after the Security Council on Monday
unanimously adopted a resolution that warns Iraq of severest
consequences if it again bars U.N. arms inspectors from suspected
sites in their search for weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
"All of the members of the Council agree that failure to do so
will result in the severest consequences for Iraq," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
In coming days and weeks, inspectors would renew their mission
to find and destroy Iraq's chemical, biological and nuclear
weapons capacity, and the missiles to deliver them.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq now has the responsibility to turn the commitment it has
made into full compliance," he concluded.
</P>
<P>
Neither Clinton nor the U.N. document spelled out what the
consequences would be if Iraq refuses weapons inspectors access to
any suspected sites. But U.S. officials have said any further
violation by Iraq would ensure strong support for military
strikes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
