<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Commercial Banks Encouraged to Aid Exporters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Thai commercial banks were
encouraged to extend more loans to local exporters as the central
bank approved the change in capital adequacy requirement, the
Bangkok Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand agreed Monday to reduce the risk weighting
of pre-shipment credits from 100 percent to 20 percent, which
means commercial banks could maintain less capital in managing
their loan portfolios.
</P>
<P>
Under the capital adequacy guideline, banks must maintain
capital funds equal to 8.5 percent of risk assets.
</P>
<P>
Risk assets, which are primarily loans, are given different
weights according to the relative risks involved.
</P>
<P>
Commercial banks had asked regulators to adjust the risk
weightings so that they could increase their credit lines to
exporters while gaining more flexibility in maintaining the
capital-to-risk assets ratio within the 8.5 percent minimum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
