<HEADLINE> China's Rural Purchasing Power to Expand Faster This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- China's vast rural market is
likely to grow faster than the urban market this year, the results
of a nationwide survey among farmers indicated.
</P>
<P>
The rural markets will further reveal their vitality and
potential this year by growing about 10 percent over last year's
1.04 trillion yuan (125.89 billion US dollars), today's China
Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The survey, arranged recently by the All China Federation of
Supply and Marketing Co-operatives, was conducted among 14,408
rural households in different parts of the country. It found that
the expenditure on everyday commodities and production materials
would continue to increase because of growing income levels last
year.
</P>
<P>
Spending on food will still be on top of farmers' shopping list
in 1998. However, as indicated by the survey, there will be
bigger increases in farmers' spending on durable goods for home
use and farming machinery as durable goods are becoming
increasingly popular among rural families. China's rural areas are
home to 72 percent of the country's 1.2 billion people.
</P>
<P>
The market for durable goods such as color TV sets,
refrigerators, VCDs and washing machines will be brisk in the
central and western areas, with rural consumer demand expected to
grow by about 17 percent, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Demand for house construction and decoration materials will be
a "hot spot" which will boost the rural market in some
regions. And farmers' demand for production materials will also
continue to grow by six percent, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 11 Banks to Fund Trade Financing in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Asia Development Bank (ADB)
and 10 international banks have agreed to lend Thailand 1 billion
US dollars to fund trade financing for local importers, a source
at the Bank of Thailand said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Finance Ministry and the banks were expected to sign
an agreement to this effect on April 1, said the source who
refused to be named.
</P>
<P>
The five-year loan, guaranteed by the Thai government, will be
disbursed through the Export-Import Bank. Terms call for an annual
interest rate of libor (London interbank offered rate) plus 0.80
percent, the source explained.
</P>
<P>
The ADB is also guaranteeing principal and interest on the loan
for the first three years, which helped lower risk premiums
significantly on the borrowing.
</P>
<P>
The fund will be used to finance raw material imports for
export production as well as post-shipment financing.
</P>
<P>
Banks participating in the ADB-initiated loan included the Bank
of Tokyo-Mitsubishi, Dai-Ichi Kangyo Asia and the Industrial Bank
of Japan.
</P>
<P>
The loan was the first taken by the Thai Finance Ministry since
the currency crisis engulfed Thailand and the region last July.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts said the approval of the loan was a sign that
confidence in the Thai economy was improving within the
international financial markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
