<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 100 Million Latin-American Children Live in Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARTAGENA, Colombia, March 2 (Xinhua) -- About 100 million
Latin American children, half of the child population in the
region, are living in complete poverty, a report from the
Inter-American Institute of the Child said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The institute, with its headquarters in Montevideo, Uruguay,
said 100 million children lack the minimal conditions to survive.
</P>
<P>
It said: "Millions of Latin American residents under the age of
18 have not escaped from oppression and misery."
</P>
<P>
The report said the judicial treatment of children in the
region was precarious because many countries had ratified the
United Nations convention on children's rights in 1989.
</P>
<P>
However, not all the nations had improved their own legislature
according to the U.N. principles. This was why Latin American
children remained poor and defenseless.
</P>
<P>
The report has been contributed to the Regional Summit for
Infancy, which is convened by the First Lady of Colombia, Jacquin
Strouss de Samper, and participated in by more than 20 first
ladies from the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
