<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Republic Sees Increased Budget Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The budget surplus of the Czech
Republic reached 4.8 billion koruna (about 145 million
U.S. dollars) during the first two months this year, Michal
Jirkovsky, a spokesman for the Financial Ministry, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Government finances are better than at any time in recent
years, Jirkovsky added.
</P>
<P>
In January and February, budget revenue reached 80.8 billion
koruna (about 2.45 billion dollars), rising by 12.7 percent over
the same period last year, with a 1-percent drop in spending, down
to 76 billion koruna (about 2.3 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the Czech Republic's deficit reached 15.7 billion
koruna (about 476 million dollars). To turn the situation around,
the Czech government adopted a series of measures at the beginning
of this year, including strict spending controls and stronger
management of tax revenues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
