<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drop in Peru's Mineral Exports Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Peru's mineral exports will
experience a 4.7 percent decline this year to 2.5 billion
U.S. dollars due primarily to a drop in metal prices in
international markets, a senior official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Manager of the National Society of Mining and Petroleum Carlos
Diez Canseco said the financial crisis in southeast Asia and the
over-supply in the second half of last year has forced the price
of copper to plummet from 99 cents per pound in 1997 to the
current 88 cents per pound, registering an 11 percent decline, the
biggest drop among all minerals.
</P>
<P>
Copper exports, which account for 40 percent of the country's
total mineral exports, are expected to fall by 7.5 percent this
year to about one billion U.S. dollars, he added.
</P>
<P>
Canseco also predicted that gold prices will fall by 10.7
percent, which currently stand at 300 U.S. dollars per
ounce. Peru's gold exports will fall by 8.1 percent to 459 million
dollars because of the price.
</P>
<P>
The consequences of falling prices are visible. Three mines
have closed indefinitely in Peru and another has closed
temporarily. Though the mines are small, their importance cannot
be underestimated, Canseco said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
