<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Considers Regulating Banks' Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the Philippines
is seriously considering capping commercial bank's interest rates
to only five percent above the 90-day treasury bill rate, the
Philippine Star reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted central bank governor Gabriel Singson as
saying that he is scheduled to meet anew this week with Bankers
Association of the Philippines President Deogracias Vistan to
discuss what other steps could be taken to reduce the banks' prime
lending rates.
</P>
<P>
If their lending rates will remain at their current level after
the meeting, Singson said the central bank may have to issue a
circular limiting the spread of the banks to just five percent.
</P>
<P>
Banks that violate the limit would face sanctions, Singson
added.
</P>
<P>
However, some economists and bankers have warned against such a
fixed interest ceiling.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Vistan said the bankers had reached a gentlemen
agreement with his association, agreeing to lower their prime
lending rates one percent every week starting February 2, but on a
voluntary basis.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the depreciation of the peso, the interest rates
in the country have been soaring in the past few months, dealing a
heavy blow to the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Despite the efforts of the central bank, the interest rates
still remained high at between 25 percent and 30 percent, forcing
hundreds of businessmen to close shops to protest against the
"extremely high" rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
