<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Province Wants Bigger Share of World Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Shandong Province in east China has
worked out a detailed program to gain a bigger share of the world
market, according to a provincial government official in charge of
foreign trade and economy.
</P>
<P>
The program is also aimed to keep the effects of the Asian
financial crisis in the local foreign trade sector to a minimum,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Shandong is one of the largest economic powers in the
country. Local products have been exported to more than 170
foreign countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
However, the about 60 percent of the local exports have gone to
neighboring countries in Asia, 30 percent have gone to the United
States and EU, while only a tiny few percent of exports have gone
to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
Under the provincial plan, in the coming few years Shandong
will continue to focus on the Asia-Pacific area as well as
neighboring and surrounding countries and regions. Meanwhile,
efforts will be made to explore markets in CIS, the Middle East,
Africa and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, by 2000 the province's exports to the
U.S and EU will reach 7 billion U.S. dollars, exports to Japan,
ROK and Southeast Asian countries will be 8 billion U.S. dollars
while 4 billion U.S. dollars worth of local products are expected
to be sold to the new markets.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government plans to issue more preferential
policies to stimulate its foreign trade sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
