<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil: Against Tobacco Consumption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- For the first time in Rio, the
annual meeting for the Latin-American committee coordinating the
control of nicotinism was inaugurated Monday and will last until
March 5.
</P>
<P>
Many Latin-American specialists and authorities in smoking
habits are attending the event and will address issues such as
reduction on tobacco consumption and avoidance of chronic diseases.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the attendants will speak about work done
by the participant countries, and programmes directed by the
Brazilian National Institute of Cancer to fight nicotinism.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization (WHO) praised the Brazilian
efforts as the most efficent actions among the Spanish and
Portuguese speaking countries to fight tobacco consumption.
</P>
<P>
According to figures from the WHO, around 30.6 million
Brazilian people are smokers, with 2.8 million of them being
persons under 20.
</P>
<P>
The National Institute of Cancer in Brazil reckons the numbers
of lung cancers will increase to 20 thousand new cases and 12.7
thousand deaths caused by the disease this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
