<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Countries to Promote Educational Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The Arab Higher Education
Conference opened here Monday with the aim of improving the
quality of education in the Arab world and setting guidelines for
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
About 1,000 government officials and representatives from 20
Arabian countries and the United Nations Educational, Scientific
and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) attended the opening ceremony
of the four-day conference.
</P>
<P>
A better future for higher education could be achieved through
the establishment of Arab universities at regional Arab levels, so
unifying the dispersed efforts in education, Saudi Prince Talal
Bin Abdel-Aziz, also president of the Gulf fund of the U.N.
Development Organizations, told the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
He said it was the joint concern and clear desire to render
higher education more efficient and responsive of the needs of the
Arab society.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi prince also called on the conference to come up with
clearly defined and practical recommendations.
</P>
<P>
The UNESCO's General Director, Eredrico Mayor, said higher
education could contribute to what must be central goal of the
21st century, culture and peace.
</P>
<P>
During the conference, the participants will address the issues
of developing the education system, the advancement of science and
scientific research, labor market development and economic needs,
the preparation of educators, funding, and academic freedom.
</P>
<P>
The conference also helps prepare for the world conference on
higher education to be held in Paris next October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
