<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Abuse of Child Labor Serious in Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARTAGENA, Colombia, March 2 (Xinhua) -- About 17 million
children between the ages of 10 and 14 are currently working in
Latin America and the Caribbean region. At least 90 percent of
them receive wages under the minimum wage level.
</P>
<P>
The figure indicates that one of every five children living in
that region is forced to become a child laborer, said Victor
Tokman, regional director of the International Labor
Organization. Tokman's report was submitted Sunday to the summit
on children's rights in Latin-America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from more than 30 countries in the region,
including 22 first ladies, took part in the three-day summit in
Cartagena, Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Also in his report, Tokman said there are more boys employed as
laborers than girls; and children living in rural areas go to work
at an earlier age than children living in cities.
</P>
<P>
The kind of work child laborers do is usually stressful and
they are grossly underpaid. The children also work long shifts of
35-46 hours per week, Tokman added.
</P>
<P>
He called for a program that would put an end to the abuse of
child labor and said a high priority should be placed on
preventing the employment of children in harsh and dangerous
positions.
</P>
<P>
The issue of child labor has topped all other topics during the
summit, including family violence, child sexual abuse and children
in armed conflicts.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the meeting, a document to prevent the abuse of
child labor is expected to be approved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
