<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Pledges Aid to Help Manila Confront Financial Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos has been
assured that the U.S. government would provide a 21-million-dollar
facility to help the Philippines implement identified measures to
confront the Asian financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Manila Bulletin reported on Tuesday that
Washington made the commitment through the U.S. Agency for
International Development, whose assistant administrator for Asia,
Kelly Kammerer, was visiting the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Ramos on Monday, Kammerer said the facility
would be a three-year technical assistance to the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
"The United States recognizes that the exceptional nature of
the recent financial turmoil in Asia requires extra efforts by
members of the international community," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kammerer urged the Ramos administration to continue
its commitment to the open-market economy.
</P>
<P>
He cited the Philippines for creating, in recent years, a
political and economic climate that has attracted investments,
accelerated growth and reduced poverty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
