<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burns Wins First World Champion in Safari Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Briton Richard Burns scored his
first win in the World Rally Championship (WRC) events Monday here
with "fantastic" feelings when standing on the start-and-end ramp
of the Safari Rally.
</P>
<P>
Burns finished with eight hours, 57 minutes and 34 seconds in
total at the WRC third round race. His average speed over the
1,063 kilometers of competitive sections was 119 kilometers per
hour, with a peak single section average of 141kph.
</P>
<P>
"I'm so, so chuffed!", the 27-year-old said.
</P>
<P>
His short hair was wet by spurting champagne, his smile full on
the face. His white Mitsubishi Carisma car, without a particle of
dust on, reflected the brilliance of the hot sun overhead.
</P>
<P>
"I can't believe it. I am totally overcome," said Burn's
co-driver Robert Reid who had tears of joy streaming down his face.
</P>
<P>
Finnish Juha Kankkunen in a Ford was second with nine hours,
seven minutes and one second, only 25 seconds ahead of teammate
Ari Vatanen, also a Finn. They are followed by Toyota's French
driver Didier Auriol, 9:12:00.
</P>
<P>
First-timers SEAT had an outstanding debut, winning the
two-liter class and finishing fifth overall through Harri
Rovanpera in 11:03:12.
</P>
<P>
Spain's Luis Climent won GP N by a huge margin with a
Mitsubishi car. He also took the seventh place on the top ten with
11:25:37.
</P>
<P>
Safari has always been by far the longest and roughest WRC
event. This time, hot weather, thick dust and rocky roads took
toll of several top-seeded drivers including Finn Tommi Makinen,
Briton Colin McRae and Spaniard Carlos Sainz.
</P>
<P>
Makinen and McRae made shock exits due to engine failure when
approaching to the end of the 1139-kilometer second leg Sunday
afternoon, at the time they were taking the first two places of
the rally.
</P>
<P>
Sainz retired Monday morning soon after his rear strut broke.
The tyre then rubbered against the damaged strut and bodywork and
caught fire. However, he tried to continue on only three wheels
until ultimately the car was unable to drag itself any further.
</P>
<P>
The three-day Safari Rally, the sole WRC event in Africa,
started Saturday and run over a total of 2339.21 kilometers, 86
kilometers shorter than that of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Safari, started in 1953 as a sport of fun for amateur drivers
keen on driving around the roads of east Africa, nowadays is
widely recognized as one of the most glamorous events on the World
Championship calendar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
