<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: 400,000 Gulf War Veterans Exposed to Uranium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- As many as 400,000 U.S. troops
may have been exposed to hazardous depleted uranium from shells
fired by U.S. tanks and aircraft during the Persian Gulf War, said
a study released Monday.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by the National Gulf War Resource Center,
estimated at least 400,000 service men and women had contact with
depleted uranium either during combat while recovering
contaminated weapons or while visiting the battleground after the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
"Veterans have been left twisting in the wind for seven years,"
said Paul Sullivan, executive director of the center that oversees
45 veterans groups. "We firmly believe this is a conservative
estimate of those exposed."
</P>
<P>
Depleted uranium is a metal residue left when natural uranium
is refined. It is used in artillery shells and bombs designed to
penetrate the armor of tanks. It also is used as a protective
shell on armored vehicles.
</P>
<P>
When a depleted uranium shell hits its target, some of the
metal burns and oxidizes into small particles. This creates an
airborne dust that, if inhaled or ingested, can be toxic in
humans.
</P>
<P>
Short term symptoms include nausea, vomiting and weakness, the
study indicated. Ingestion of large amounts of dust can cause
kidney and liver damage, depressed immune system and cancer.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon office investigating Gulf War illnesses has
insisted that only 27 soldiers had possibly been exposed to
depleted uranium. But the Office of the Special Assistant for Gulf
War Illnesses admitted that thousands of troops may have been
exposed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
