<HEADLINE> Greece Voices Concern Over Kosovo Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Greece Monday voiced its concern
over the current situation in the Yugoslav region of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In an announcement issued Monday, the Greek Foreign Ministry
said that Athens would promote all initiatives in order to achieve
immediate commencement of talks between the parties concerned "so
as to find a solution with which the sovereignty and
unity-integrity of Yugoslavia as well as the rights of the
Albanian majority in Kosovo will be respected."
</P>
<P>
As a latest development, a Yugoslav Interior Ministry police
patrol was ambushed last Saturday in Glogovac, Kosovo, resulting
in the death of four policemen and 16 attackers.
</P>
<P>
Greece has said that it opposes Kosovo's independence from
Yugoslavia and respects the borders of Yugoslavia, coupled with
prospects for wide-ranging autonomy for Kosovo where 90 percent of
the 1.9 million population are made up of Albanians.
</P>
<P>
In January this year, Greece offered to host a meeting between
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, Albanian Prime Minister
Fatos Nano and the leader of the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo,
Ibrahim Rugova, to help resolve the Kosovo problem which often
leads to violence due to renewed calls by the Albanian minority
for independence from Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Meets Allies on Possible Action Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- As the U.N. Security Council is
preparing to adopt a resolution on a U.N. deal with Iraq over
weapons inspections, U.S. officials met with ambassadors of over
30 countries here Monday to discuss continued preparations for
possible military force should Iraq fail to comply with the deal.
</P>
<P>
Under-Secretary of State for Political Affairs Thomas Pickering
and Acting Assistant Secretary of State for Political-Military
Affairs Eric Newsom "emphasized the importance of continued
coalition preparations," the State Department said.
</P>
<P>
It said the United States hoped the agreement negotiated with
Baghdad last month by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan would
provide access to all suspected sites where weapons of mass
destruction may be hidden.
</P>
<P>
"But as recent events have made clear, it is necessary that the
international community remain prepared to act forcefully it
Baghdad fails to comply with its commitments and obligations," it
added in a statement.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials refused to list all the countries represented at
Monday's meeting. Britain has been Washington's leading supporter.
Other NATO nations, Australia, Argentina and some East European
states have also promised help.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said the United States
hoped the resolution would send "s strong signal to Iraq that if
it does violate this agreement... that they understand what the
consequences would be."
</P>
<P>
"We have made clear what those consequences would be, and we
have also made clear that we don't see the need to return to the
Security Council," Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"And we also have very clear assurances from key governments
that they would understand and be more supportive of that decision
if it comes to that," he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. armed forces buildup in the Gulf will stay in place
and operate at a high tempo for at least the next 90 days while
U.N. inspectors resume their search for Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction, senior military official here said.
</P>
<P>
They said the Pentagon believed it would take that long for
inspectors to visit "test-case" sites, such as presidential
compounds suspected of holding components for biological and
chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will travel to Europe and
Canada for a six-day visit. She will discuss with U.S. key allies
like Britain, France, Germany Italy and Canada. And possible
action against Iraq will come up during her talks with officials
of these countries.
</P>
<P>
"I would fully expect them to go over the Iraq issue in great
detail and plan for possible contingencies if past is prologue and
Iraq does violate the agreement," Rubin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quebec's Johnson Steps Down As Liberal Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Daniel Johnson, leader of the
Liberal Party of Quebec, announced Monday that he will step down
to give his party a better chance of winning the next provincial
election.
</P>
<P>
"Today, with the issues of the next election taking shape, I
think the time has come to announce that I will be leaving public
life," Johnson told a press conference broadcast live on
television.
</P>
<P>
"The election will be extremely important for all Quebecers and
I am convinced that the Quebec Liberal party will win it," he said
from Quebec City, capital of Canada's French-speaking province of
Quebec.
</P>
<P>
Johnson, 53, has been the leader of Quebec's opposition Liberal
Party for four years. He will remain as leader until a successor
is chosen.
</P>
<P>
His party was defeated in a 1993 provincial election by the
ruling Parti Quebecois, which has been trying to separate the
province from the rest of Canada.
</P>
<P>
Monday's announcement will likely mean that Quebec Premier
Lucien Bouchard will put off an election that he had been hinting
could be held as early as this Spring, according to analysts here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
