produced a total of 763,000 tons of newsprint in January, down
4.2 percent from that of a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian Pulp and Paper Association said Monday that the
industry's operating rate also dipped to 87 percent of its
capacity from 93 percent in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
"During the month, total shipments from Canadian producers
declined by 7.6 percent, with deliveries to the U.S. dropping by
2.0 percent and those to offshore markets by 27.3 percent," the
association said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Canada's domestic deliveries grew by 7.7
percent over January 1997.
</P>
<P>
At the end of January, Canadian newsprint producers held
336,000 tons in inventory, which represents an increase of 82,000
tons from the end of December.
</P>
<P>
"It should be noted that producers' stocks typically increase
in January," it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
