<HEADLINE> U.S. Says No Plans for further Food Aid to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States has no plans
to send more food to the Democratic People's Repubic of Korea
(DPRK), the State Department said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We have no plans for further assistance," Spokesman for the
Department James Rubin told a briefing. But he added: "We
encourage other members of the international community to
contribute."
</P>
<P>
The DPRK's Korean Central News Agency (KCNA) has said that
grain rations were cut in January and February but supplies were
still expected to run out by mid-March.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the announcement by KCNA was "not a surprise to us"
and the U.N. World Food Program had predicted such a situation.
</P>
<P>
The United States has pledged 200,000 tones of food aid this
year for the famine-stricken DPRK, and the first shipment of
22,000 tons is expected to arrive in the country around the
beginning of April.
</P>
<P>
The World Food Program is currently supplying 98,000 tons of
grain to DPRK. It also launched a new international appeal in
January for 658,000 tons of food to help 7. 47 mil in the country
-- about a third of the population.  
</P>
</TEXT>
