<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Current Account Posts Big Deficit in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Canada's current account returned
to a deficit of 17.0 billion dollars (11.9 billion U.S. dollars)
in 1997, following a small surplus in 1996, Statistics Canada
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The change in 1997 was chiefly due to a large reduction in the
surplus on goods and, to a lesser extent, to a higher deficit on
investment income," the statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Canada's surplus on goods drooped by 17.6 billion
dollars to 23.4 billion dollars, as imports outpaced exports for
the first time in six years.
</P>
<P>
Strength in Canadian demand caused imports to rise across a
wide spectrum of goods, while exports surged mainly in auto,
machinery and equipment, industrial materials and energy products.
</P>
<P>
As foreign multinational corporations earned higher profits in
Canada, the country's deficit on investment income showed a rise
of 4.1 billion dollars in 1997 to a high of 31.9 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, foreign corporations reinvested the bulk of these
profits into their Canadian operations in 1997, the agency said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
