<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-02 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, Central Asian Countries to Cooperate in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and four Central Asian
countries announced Monday that they will cooperate closely in
exploiting the Caspian oil, the Anatolia News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministers of Turkey, Azerbaijan, Georgia, Kazakhstan
and Turkmenistan discussed the issue on Sunday and Monday in
Istanbul, the largest city of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
"The ministers confirmed the significance of transporting these
resources to international markets in safety through economically
and commercially feasible multiple oil and natural gas
pipelines," said a communique issued at the end of the
ministerial meeting.
</P>
<P>
It added that the five countries agree that a pipeline
route through Azerbaijan, Georgia as well as Turkey will be a
wise choice for oil transportation.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem said that the planned
Baku-Ceyhan pipeline, which has 468 kilometers in Azerbaijan,
225 kilometers in Georgia and 1037 kilometers in Turkey, has
gained general support of the five countries.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that this will be realized some day. But, still,
we should not raise our expectations too high," he said.
</P>
<P>
Officials closed to the meeting said that Azerbaijan and
Georgia expressed full support for the Baku-Ceyhan project put
forwarded by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan, however, said that they favored the Baku-Ceyhan
project but that they could support it only if the financial
and technical problems involved get resolved.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been playing an active role in exploiting the
abundant Caspian oil in order to meet its rapidly increasing
energy demands and also earn foreign exchange through supplying
pipelines.
</P>
<P>
As an energy-starving country, Turkey has to import oil and
natural gas from its neighboring countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
