<DOCNO> XIE19980303.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-02 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "We Want Peace," Israelis Say </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAQOURA, Jordan, March 2 (Xinhua) -- "We want peace," said the
Israelis who came here Monday to attend a eulogy ceremony for
seven Israeli school girls killed near the Jordan-Israel border by
a Jordanian soldier on March 13, 1997.
</P>
<P>
"We come to visit 'the area of peace'," said Yossi Atiyas,
whose 14-year-old cousin Meiri Yeela was shot dead by Ahmad Al
Dakamseh with six other schoolmates when they were touring the
border area.
</P>
<P>
Atiyas attended Monday's ceremony together with 14 other
relatives of Yeela's family at the invitation of the Jordanian
government. "Peace is good. We all expect peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 450 Israelis, including all the family members of
the seven school girls, arrived at the daisy-covered highland to
commemorate the victims.
</P>
<P>
Meghldish Aliel's grandmother burst into tears as soon as she
got off the bus, saying her granddaughter was killed by "a crazy
man."
</P>
<P>
"What we say is that she was dead before the gun of a crazy
man, but what we do not want to say is that she was dead due to
the long-time conflicts between Arab (countries) and Israel," said
Aliel's grandfather, who was supporting his wife from falling down
to the ground.
</P>
<P>
Relatives lined up on the slope where the girls were shot and
killed, for making fun of the soldier praying. Some cried, some
murmured and others stared at the yellow flowers covering the
slope.
</P>
<P>
Among the mourners was a 10-year-old boy Sagi Musay, whose
cousin Ptichi Sivan was one of the victims.
</P>
<P>
"I loved Sivan. We used to play together, shop together and go
to school together. When she was killed, I lost one of my best
friends," he said.
</P>
<P>
"She was killed because she was Jewish. There are conflicts
between the Jewish people and the Arab people. There is no
peace. We expect peace," said the boy.
</P>
<P>
The girls teacher, Yafa Shukrun, made a speech soon after the
ceremony started. She expressed hope that the Jewish and Arab
peoples will co-exist in peace.
</P>
<P>
"We share the water of a river and we share the scent of daisy
flowers, I hope we could bury the axe and strive for peace," she
said.
</P>
<P>
The Yarmouk River flows between Jordan and Israel and Baqoura,
where the shooting occurred, stands beside the river.
</P>
<P>
Representative of the Jordanian army Major General Abed Khalaf
Najada told the mourners that the armies of the two countries have
been coordinating closely with each other in the past months to
prevent such violence from happening again.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein and Crown Prince Hassan have contacted with
Israeli leaders several times to arrange the ceremony, which was
to show Jordan's determination to avert new violence and establish
peace between the two peoples, he said.
</P>
<P>
"All of us will do everything to make better peace both in
Israel and Jordan," he added.
</P>
<P>
A similar eulogy ceremony was held in Nahraim, Israel, just
across the border, during the day, which was attended by Jordanian
Chief Chaberlain Raad Ben Zeid and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The killer Dakamseh was sentenced to death last year and the
victims' families received compensation from Hussein
himself. However, the court ruling and the compensation triggered
strong opposition in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994 and was
believed to be Israel's best friend among its many hostile Arab
neighbors. Some Jordanians, however, are reluctant to go along
with the government line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
