<HEADLINE> Egypt Warns Against Manipulating World Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Egypt on Monday sounded alarm
against the tendency of big powers manipulating the United Nations
and international relations sliding into anarchy, the Middle East
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a symposium opened here Monday, Egyptian Foreign
Minister Amr Moussa expressed regret that the U.N. is being
controlled by "forces which care only for their interests and do
not abide by international legitimacy."
</P>
<P>
"We are passing through a period marked by duality of
resolutions and selective application of these resolutions, thus
under-estimating international legitimacy and law," Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
He added that since the end of the cold war, there is "only one
country" capable of applying influence on the international scene
and tampering with the international will.
</P>
<P>
"It interferes in the international decision-making process in
such a way that does not spare the Middle East," he said,
apparently referring to the United States.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., despite international call for a peaceful settlement
of the Iraqi crisis over weapons inspections, had repeatedly
threatened to use force against Baghdad before U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan brokered a deal with Iraq late last
month.
</P>
<P>
Even after the signing of the deal, Washington decided to keep
its warplanes, air-craft carriers and other combat ships in the
Gulf region and insisted on punishing Iraq if it again breaches
signed accords and U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Moussa warned that challenges facing the Arab world have
redoubled since the Arab-Israeli war in June 1967, as more Arab
lands have been occupied since then and international politics
poised to protect "world conglomerates."
</P>
<P>
Moussa called for restructuring the U.N., stressing the
importance of the world organization to Third World countries in
particular. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
